<HEAD>Bush Meets with Teamsters Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> met Tuesday with leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> to thank the union officials for their support in his election to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, according to a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman. The meeting included six Teamsters officials who are scheduled to go on trial next month as the result of a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> civil suit accusing them of racketeering, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Wednesday editions. The brief session was held in the office of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s incoming chief of staff, said <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The meeting had not been publicly announced. `` The Teamsters people were meeting with <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> and the president-elect simply stopped by briefly. The purpose was to thank them for their support during the election campaign,'' she said. The meeting was set up by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said. The Post reported that <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> noted the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> case against the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> but said any discussion of the case would be inappropriate in the meeting. Last June, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> filed suit in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, charging that the Teamsters were infiltrated by organized crime and urging a federal court to put the union under government trusteeship. The case is scheduled to go to trial Feb. 27 and the 18 defendants include <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> and others in the group who met with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, the Post reported. In 1981 and 1985, after the election of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had appeared at the union's board meetings during inaugural week to thank the organization for endorsing the Reagan-Bush ticket. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, the meeting Tuesday was in lieu of a public appearance by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at a Teamsters' board meeting, which union officials had sought.
