<SECOND>PM-Nunsearch,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thoroughly Modern Nuns Audition for Part in Hit Musical</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 She wore black stretch pants, a sequined vest and a top hat. Sister <PERSON> Rena </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> did not look like a nun. Sister <PERSON> Brigid </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> looked the part in full Carmelite habit and veil. But she did n't act it: She took to center stage like a veteran performer and played snappy spoons to a bluegrass tune. Life imitated show business Monday as about a dozen real-life nuns showed up at the Charles Street Playhouse to audition for the musical `` Nunsense,'' a gentle spoof of convent life. Judging their performances was a panel of nun-impersonators, the show's regular cast. The habit-wearing actresses sing, clown and even tapdance in an off-beat comedy about nuns who stage a talent show to raise money to bury four of their sisters who died of botulism and are being temporarily stored in the convent freezer. The five real-life nuns judged most talented will each be given a cameo role in the show for one week in February or March. The producers billed the audition as `` Nunsearch'' and advertised for `` real nuns'' in Catholic and secular newspapers. They have promised to donate $ 2 from every ticket sold for the special shows to a charity chosen by the performing nun. `` We're constantly getting mail from nuns and priests who love the show,'' said co-producer <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Biller </PERSON>. `` We're doing it to raise some money for charity and also of course to get publicity.'' `` Nunsense,'' written by <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Goggin </PERSON>, has played in 30 <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities since its 1985 debut, <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> said. It's now playing in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, is entering its third season in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, he said. Some of the nuns who auditioned said they had dreamed of stage careers before taking the veil. `` I always wanted to go to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>,'' said Sister <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuhrman </PERSON>, 37, who works with the elderly in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` But I just knew I belonged in the convent.'' `` When you get past 30, you start to say, I wish I'd done this, I wish I'd done that,'' she said. `` Even if I do n't make the part, at least I can say I auditioned for an off-Broadway show.'' Sister <PERSON> Marie </PERSON>, who confessed to sweaty palms, delivered a comic monologue while her sisters and her mother superior cheered her bravery. `` You see nuns on TV, they're such stereotypes of pious, holier than thou types, and they're such stuffed shirts and prudes,'' she said. `` We're not all that stuffy.'' Sister <PERSON> Rena </PERSON> was a professional dancer and even owned her own dance studio before entering the Sisters of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joseph </LOCATION> convent at age 28. Now grey-haired, she performed a jazz number to the tune of `` City Lights'' _ complete with shoulder rolls, high-kicks, and the splits for a finale. Sister <PERSON> Brigid </PERSON> of the Carmelite Sisters for the Aged and Infirm in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> said she decided to perform her wooden spoon routine in hopes of attracting more young women to her order. `` We are getting acolytes and novitiates, but not as many as we did,'' she said, adding that she believes that nuns' participation in a professional musical will show young women `` we're not just behind the walls doing our work. There is joy.''
