<FIRST>r a BC-Opera     01-17 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jessye Norman, Samuel Ramey Electrify Met</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two giant talents of the opera world, soprano <PERSON> Jessye </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> and bass <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramey </PERSON>, electrified a Metropolitan Opera audience, many of whom usually would be happy to stay away from one-act operas by <PERSON> Bartok </PERSON> and <PERSON> Schoenberg </PERSON>. On Monday night the two Americans sang <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> and Bluebeard, in English, in a striking, theatrical new production of <PERSON> Bartok </PERSON>'s `` Bluebeard's Castle. And Miss <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> did the entire job _ a tour de force _ in the Met's premiere of <PERSON> Schoenberg </PERSON>'s `` Erwartung,'' which can be translated `` Expectation.'' Both Miss <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Ramey </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Colby </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, have big voices, with beautiful, lush tone in all parts of the register. However much vocal control, breath, volume or musicianship is called for, they're equal to it and there's plenty more where that came from. Their characterizations _ as set by <PERSON> Goran </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarvefelt </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Bolinas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, making his Met debut _ were right on target. As the curtain goes up, newlyweds <PERSON> Bluebeard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> have just arrived at Bluebeard's dark castle. As <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> asks for the key to one door after another, she goes from a cheery, inquisitive girl to being imperially demanding. <PERSON> Bluebeard </PERSON> goes from pride to cringing, knowing what's coming and dreading it. As <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> opens doors and takes from him parts of his past, <PERSON> Bluebeard </PERSON> takes off parts of his garb, starting with the dark glasses that have given his white face a skeletal look, through fur collar, coat, cloak, shirt and finally wig. The remarkable set is by <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Schavernoch </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Gmunden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, making his Met debut. Side walls extend inward, meeting in a V, so that one does n't have to sit in the center to see the walls. One wall folds back, when <PERSON> Bluebeard </PERSON> shows <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> the world. The other wall has the doors, through which implements of torture, a battering ram, a big pile of gold and jewels and a tall tree appear. When the last door opens, revealing the three wives Bluebeard murdered, they appear as zombies who crawl forth and walk, silently. <PERSON> Bluebeard </PERSON> puts the cloak of death on <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> and she follows them, moving like a queen. Her red gown and cloak were magnificent. Lore <PERSON> Haas </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, who has worked extensively with <PERSON> Schavernoch </PERSON>, also was making her Met debut. When `` Bluebeard's Castle'' was performed by the Met in 1974, the concept was nothing like this. It was almost a concert. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> conducted with deliberate care. The orchestral music contains some chilling moments. Miss <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>'s singing was just as remarkable in `` Erwartung.'' But it's a letdown after the other opera. It's sung in German and the plot is impenetrable. `` The Woman'' is searching for a man in a forest. Once she finds a corpse and puts his hand on her skin to warm it. The next time she's at that part of the stage, the corpse is gone. Is she crazy? Did she kill him? Is she hallucinating? The same design team used the other opera's backdrop, plus three autumn trees, a park bench, flowers, candles and a grand piano. The only thing we objected to all evening was the piano and Miss Norman running between it and the bench. `` Erwartung'' is confusing enough. The Feb. 1 performance will be videotaped for showing March 31 on PBS.
