<HEAD>Ailing Soviet Teen-Ager Seeks Treatment in Phoenix</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet teen-ager unable to find a cure in her native country for a heart condition she has had since birth arrived Monday for treatment and a tearful welcome from relatives she had never seen. Seventeen-year-old <PERSON> Oksana </PERSON> <PERSON> Hlebkyna </PERSON> received a traditional Ukrainian greeting _ a loaf of round, wholesome bread, garnished with a container of salt, and red and white flowers _ when she was wheeled into the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> airport terminal. Six youngsters clad in traditional Ukrainian garb _ white blouses with intricate embroidery on the sleeves and dark skirts or trousers _ sang for Miss <PERSON> Hlebkyna </PERSON>. `` The name of the song is ` Long Live,''' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosola </PERSON>, 69, who arrived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1955 along with his wife, <PERSON> Kateryna </PERSON>, the ailing young woman's great-aunt. Mrs. <PERSON> Rosola </PERSON>, relaying the teen-ager's thanks, said the trip to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was Miss <PERSON> Hlebkyna </PERSON>'s most coveted wish. Mrs. <PERSON> Rosola </PERSON> said surgeon <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Diethrich </PERSON> and administrator <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> and Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ariz </LOCATION>., helped make arrangements <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> said it was n't immediately known what doctors could do for Miss Hlebkyna `` We are not able to state what kind of medical problem she has, because we do n't know,'' Ms. <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> said. `` Most of the documents we received were in Russian, and none of us here speak Russian. Tomorrow morning, she will begin to undergo medical evaluation.'' Miss <PERSON> Hlebkyna </PERSON> and her mother, <PERSON> Wladymyra </PERSON> <PERSON> Lobkowa </PERSON>, made the trip from their hometown of <LOCATION> Stryj </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last week and flew to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Sunday, Ms. <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> and Air West airlines flew the pair for free, Ms. <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> said. Doctors at the AHI `` are prepared to donate their services if need be ... We are not making an issue of the financial arrangements,'' said Miss <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, the institute's director of acute intervention and transplant services. She said institute officials had been told <PERSON> Oksana </PERSON>'s condition was life-threatening and was affecting her lungs. `` From what we understand, she has a very abnormal heart disease. It's one that she's had since birth, and it's not feasible that she live with it,'' Miss <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said. The <PERSON> Rosolas </PERSON> left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> almost 45 years ago, captives of a German army. Mrs. <PERSON> Rosola </PERSON> said she did not learn until seven years ago of her grand-niece's heart problems. That knowledge spurred her efforts, ever more intense, to find a way to bring Miss Hlebkyna to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.
