<HEAD>Study: Male Hormones Are Good For Men's Hearts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Doctors have long recognized the power of female sex hormones to keep women's hearts healthy. Now there's evidence that abundant levels of testosterone may be good for men's `` It's attractive to think that being male is good for men and being female is good for women,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett-Connor </PERSON>, a physician at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. Estrogen, the female hormone, is believed to one of the key differences between the sexes that explains why women typically live seven to eight years longer than men. <PERSON> Barrett-Connor </PERSON> presented evidence Monday that men with high levels of testosterone, the male hormone, are in better shape than those with relatively low levels. Whether this means they are more likely to escape heart attacks is still unclear. Her work, presented Monday at a meeting of the American <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, is based on a followup of 5,000 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> residents who were first examined in 1972. She found that men with high testosterone also have higher levels of high density lipoprotein, or HDL, the so-called good cholesterol that protects people from heart attacks. They also have lower blood pressure and are less likely to be overweight. `` In other words, testosterone is good for men,'' she said. However, despite these attributes that would seem to lower the risk of heart disease, there was no clear evidence that the men with higher testosterone actually lived longer. <PERSON> Barrett-Connor </PERSON> noted that the body's levels of sex hormones fluctuate throughout the day. And since her research was based on just one blood sample, it might not have accurately identified differences between the men's hormone levels. She also noted that even if testosterone turns out to be good for men's hearts, she does not advocate taking extra doses of the hormone. She said another major study has begun to see what effect estrogen pills have on women's risk of heart attacks after they go through menopause, when their bodies' natural production of the chemical drops sharply. Some of the women will take estrogen alone, while others will get a combination of estrogen and progestin. Estrogen by itself can increase the risk of uterine cancer. But while the estrogen and progestin combination eliminates this hazard, some doctors fear that the extra progestin wipes out estrogen's benefits for the heart. Among other research presented Monday: _ Dr <PERSON> Redford </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> said that anger, not impatience, is the key element of Type A behavior that raises the risk of heart disease. He said that those with a heart attack-prone personality are more likely to get angry, to become suspicious of other people's motives and to show their hostility toward others. _ According to Dr. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Katon </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION>, panic attacks and depression are frequently mistaken for heart disease, especially among young and middle-aged women During panic attacks, people may gasp for breath, grow dizzy, tremble, feel chest pain and believe they are going to die. _ Strokes occur in two or three of every 100,000 children Dr. <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aram </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Rainbow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Babies </ORGANIZATION> and Children's Hospital in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> has found that when the stroke is limited to one side of the brain, these youngsters grow to have normal intelligence. However, they may have varying degrees of other problems, including physical weakness on one side and trouble reading and talking. _ Dr <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> reported that cocaine use is becoming a major cause of strokes in young adults. Studies at one hospital found it to be the single greatest cause of strokes in those under age 40.
</TEXT>
