<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Riot Breaks Out After Police Shoot At Suspect</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with five grafs to recast and UPDATE with store burning
and suspects both black men. Picks up 6th graf, `Four people...'. INSERTS
one graf after 14th graf, `The driver' to UPDATE with age of victim, and
with police refusing to divulge race of officers involved. Picks up 15th
graf, `A crowd...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MH13, MH16, NY61, NY65, LaserColor MH17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crowds burned cars and a store, looted and threw rocks at officers in a black neighborhood Monday after police shot at black suspects during a chase that ended with one man dead and another injured. About 125 police officers in riot gear closed off an area about 17 blocks by nine blocks in the impoverished <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION> neighborhood just north of downtown, which has been the site of major racial strife in the past. <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Xavier </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> declared the riot `` contained'' about five hours later. But late Monday, there was still sporadic gunfire and looting, according to television reports. School officials announced five schools in the area would be closed Tuesday. City Manager <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Odio </PERSON> said prominent black community leaders had been called to walk the streets Monday night seeking calm. Several officers and bystanders were hit by rocks and bottles, police said. At least two cars were set afire and two news vehicles attacked with rocks, authorities said. An auto parts store burned after firefighters were shot at and had to leave the area, police said. Four people, including one police officer, were treated for lacerations and minor injuries at <ORGANIZATION> Jackson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, and released, said spokesman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Fallon </PERSON>. Other officers were treated at the scene, police said. `` All of a sudden they threw a big huge rock right on the side of the driver. I blocked it with my elbow. They were yelling ` Get that white woman out of the car,''' said <PERSON> Lourdes </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiz-Toledo </PERSON>, a 27-year-old WCIX-TV reporter. Miss Ruiz-Toledo, who had stayed in her car while an anchorman and camerman got out, said she drove a block away and was rescued by an officer who led her from the car behind a plastic riot shield. A waitress said her windshield was shattered by a five-pound concrete block when she drove through the area on her way home from work. `` I had no idea it was going on,'' said <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Worthington </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. `` There were about 20 kids all throwing things. I was worried that I was going to be hurt. I did n't see any cops around there.'' Later Monday, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> police were placed on full alert, with overnight shifts called in early, and the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Highway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Patrol </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> police placed on standby. The incident began about 5:45 p.m. on the <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> holiday when police started chasing a motorcycle with two possible robbery suspects, said Sgt. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazur </PERSON>. Police started shooting, and the motorcycle ran into a car, <PERSON> Mazur </PERSON> said. The driver of the motorcycle died at the scene, said police Chief <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, who would n't say whether the cause was the crash or police gunfire. A motorcycle passenger was hospitalized, along with others in the vehicle involved in the wreck, police said, without giving identities. The 21-year-old dead suspect and his passenger were both black men, said police, who refused to divulge the race of the officers involved in the chase. A crowd of about 50 to 75 people gathered at the accident scene in the <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION> section and started throwing rocks and bottles, <PERSON> Mazur </PERSON> said. By several hours later, he said, the situation had become `` very volatile'' and a riot control plan was put into effect. `` I obviously can assure you we will have a full investigation,'' <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think there's ever been a situatuion where quicker action has been taken by city governance.'' During three days of rioting in the <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION> section in 1982, arsonists torched buildings and mobs broke into stores, causing millions of dollars worth of damage. The riot was sparked by the fatal shooting of a black man by a Cuban-born police officer. A police internal affairs report in 1985 concluded that the officer was justified in using deadly force. In 1980, racial violence in adjacent <LOCATION> Liberty </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> left 18 people dead, 400 injured and $ 100 million in damage. That rioting occurred after an all-white jury acquitted several <LOCATION> Miami-Dade </LOCATION> police officers of manslaughter in the beating death of a black businessman. The latest incident comes as <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> is trying to polish its image for an influx of visitors for the Super Bowl on Sunday. The scene of the disturbance was at least 10 miles from <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stadium </PERSON> in north <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, the site of the Super Bowl. But the <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bengals </ORGANIZATION> are staying less than a mile away at the Omni Hotel. The <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arena </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Basketball </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has a game scheduled Tuesday, is on the edge of <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION>.
