<HEAD>Dollar Surges In Japan; Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar surged against the Japanese yen Tuesday, while investors reacted to the weaker yen by pushing share prices lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar eased in the afternoon to close at 127.70 yen, up 1.05 yen from Friday's close of 126.65 yen, after opening at 127.93 yen and surging to peak at 128.15 yen in early morning trading. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues dipped 70.86 points, or 0.23 percent, to close at 31,227.52. Finance Minister <PERSON> Tatsuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Murayama </PERSON> attributed the dollar's strength to the difference in key interest rates between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and to reported statements by West German monetary authorities that the dollar's current level is acceptable. <PERSON> Murayama </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> will not intervene to stem the dollar's rise because `` the situation does not require imediate countermeasures.'' Currency traders said the dollar's remarkable strength against the yen followed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's bullish advance in overseas markets overnight. The dollar closed Monday in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at 128.05 yen and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at 128.10 yen. Traders said the dollar also was strong because of reduced chances for central bank intervention in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> due to national holidays. Many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> traders were absent from the market Monday