<HEAD>Shoshone Set Back In Land Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Western Shoshone Indians have vowed to press their claim to full grazing rights on a half-million acres of land despite an appeals court ruling limiting the number of horses and cows they can have. `` This is n't the end to litigation. We do n't consider this issue resolved,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leubben </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shoshone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` Only <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can resolve the Western Shoshone land issue.'' The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday reversed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s September 1986 order that gave sisters <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dann </PERSON>, members of the Shoshone tribe, the right to graze cattle and horses at their 180-acre ranch in north-central <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Crescent </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> had ruled the <ORGANIZATION> Danns </ORGANIZATION> had aboriginal and treaty rights to graze their livestock on 530,000 acres without being regulated by federal agencies or paying grazing fees. The appellate ruling limits the <ORGANIZATION> Danns </ORGANIZATION> to grazing 26 cows and 79 horses, the number their parents had on the land when the 1934 Taylor Grazing Act took effect. The sisters currently have 768 cows and 850 horses. A tearful <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dann </PERSON> said at a news conference Monday she has no plans to reduce the herd. `` I'm not really afraid of going to jail because I believe I'm right,'' she said The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government sued the <ORGANIZATION> Danns </ORGANIZATION> for trespassing in 1974 to prevent them from using the land for grazing. The 14-year-old case has been argued three times in federal court in <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>, twice in the appeals court and once before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The sisters claim that an 1863 treaty with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> gives them the right to use the land for grazing. The government contends that the Western Shoshone lost its ancestral land in 1979 when the <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claims </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> awarded the tribe $ 26 million for the acreage. The Indians have refused to accept the money. `` This land was never given by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to us. It is the Creator's land,'' <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dann </PERSON> said Monday. `` The Creator put us on this land,'' she said. We were not placed here by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> government. Our livelihood is tied to this land. They wanted to do away with our livelihood. They're trying to destroy our beliefs, our culture.'' <PERSON> Luebben </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, said he would continue to argue the case in federal court, but added he would try other avenues. `` Considering this decision by the <ORGANIZATION> 9th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Shoshone </LOCATION> people are going to have to appeal to the public and to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Luebben </PERSON> said. `` We consider this decision to be wrong and extremely unjust,'' he said. `` There is still institutional racism in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.''
