<HEAD>Education Secretary, NEA President Urge Excellence for Minorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of Education <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> said minority students are getting an inferior education because of a lack of minority teachers. <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> on Monday called the shortage a matter of `` true urgency,'' pointing out that 30 percent of the nation's students are minorities, while only 13 percent of the educators are. `` Today, the person that takes roll ... and assigns work ... is usually an Anglo teacher, doing the best he can do,'' <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> said in the keynote address to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recruitment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION>. `` In the eyes of some minority students, knowledge and education are equated with whites, and perhaps ... minority students believe education belongs to one group or another,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> said earlier Monday that the minority student population is expected to increase in the 1990s as the number of minority teachers in public schools drops to 3 percent. <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> said a shortage of minority teachers will threaten the system because it deprives minority students of positive role models and `` creates an educational deficit'' for whites because it gives `` them a distorted view of the world ... and valuable contact with teachers who offer dramatic proof that adversity can be overcome and that the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream is not a myth.'' <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> said more minority teachers must be recruited, and that recruitment must begin in elementary schools by encouraging minorities in academia. He also said parents should work with and encourage their children during the pre-school years. `` If we educators made it a top priority to enlist the aid of parents, think what a difference it would make,'' he said. `` We must help all parents create a home environment that supports achievement and learning. Too often in low-income homes, education is undervalued.'' <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> noted an anthropological study that found students at a predominantly black <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, high school were limiting their academic success `` so their peers wo n't think they are acting white.'' The teachers union president said educators `` have to do something to ensure that our children do n't think this way,'' and said schools should `` develop courses and programs aimed at helping build self-esteem.'' <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> said students must be told, `` It's OK to be smart, to use your abilities and excel.''
