<SECOND>PM-Overtown-Scene,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>In The Heart Of Overtown: A Smoldering Rage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Overtown Disturbance, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 When <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION> neighborhood erupted in flames Monday night, city leaders immediately attempted to calm fears by talking to angry residents. City Commissioner <PERSON> Rosario </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was escorted on a tour behind the roadblocks by two police officers and accompanied by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> newsman <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Lester </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By WILL LESTER</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rosario </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was looking for a better understanding of the black rage that descended upon <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> on the day that honors the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. The Cuban-born city commissioner found her answers early today on a dark corner of 20th St. and NW 3rd Ave., in the heart of <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> Guy's Auto Parts had burned to a shell. A torched car was turned on its side. The riot started after by a motorcyclist's death Monday night. At least two officers were pursuing the motorcycle for an alleged traffic violation. One of the officers fired a shot, the motorcycle crashed into a moving car, killing the cycle's 21-year-old driver, police said. Police refused to say whether he was hit by the bullet. Wary police in riot gear kept automatic rifles poised, occasionally dropping the barrel toward any rapid movement. On the corner was a group of about 15 young black men: angry, nervous _ watching every police move. The 43-year-old Mrs. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, just over 5 feet tall in her pumps and wearing a bright red pants and top, walked over. What caused this to happen? she asked. `` How can a person shoot a guy riding a motorcycle?'' replied one man, who would not identify himself. `` Do something about the ones that got the guns.'' As his voice rose, the others lost their shyness. The crowd began to grow. A young shirtless teen-ager stepped forward. `` The blacks have been here since I do n't know when,'' he said. `` But 10,000 Cubans a year ... they get jobs just like that. And now the Nicaraguans ... `` <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> officials have been providing shelter at a stadium for about 250 Nicaraguans seeking political asylum. A stone clattered to the pavement and several police rifles leveled at the crowd. `` Do n't you murder him,'' came a cry from another teen. `` We're coming to your homes if there's another murder. As the anger grew, police quietly urged Mrs. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> into a waiting car. During the ride through the streets of <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION> with two officers and a reporter, Mrs. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> got the scare of the night when her car approached a group of heavily armed policeman. The police dropped behind the car doors and leveled pistols directly at Mrs. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and the driver, Officer <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Carvil </PERSON>. <PERSON> Carvil </PERSON> placed the blue police light on the dash and the pistols dropped. Gunfire crackled in the early morning hours amid the housing projects, and officers shouted reports of `` Molotov cocktails.'' One Latin man living in a project with his wife was reportedly beaten on his front porch, officers said. Mrs. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and other city leaders had hoped this week's Super Bowl would polish up the image of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, a one-time tropical paradise, tarnished by race riots in 1980 and 1982, the flood of refugees from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> in 1980 and the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> drug wars throughout the decade. But she admitted the opportunity was fast slipping away. `` It's extremely unfortunate that it's happening now,'' she said. And she found more anger than she'd expected. `` I was surprised by the depth of anger,'' she said. `` We'll be talking to community leaders later today.''
