<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s battles for voting rights were remembered as the first black county commissioners elected in 112 years were sworn in by <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s first black federal judge. `` We bring home to <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> the harvest of the Martin Luther King voting rights act,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge U.W. <PERSON> Clemon </PERSON>, who administered the oath of office Monday to the three blacks and two whites in the county's new government. The election of the first blacks to the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> since Reconstruction followed 10 years of legal combat that abolished the old at-large election system which had kept the panel all white for more than a century. Under the new election plan, commissioners are elected from five districts, three with large or nominal black voting majorities. <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, with a population of 55,000, is about 56 percent black. The three black commissioners _ <PERSON> Erskine </PERSON> <PERSON> Minor </PERSON>, D.L. <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> and <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Varner </PERSON> _ were sworn in along with white commissioners <PERSON> Deans </PERSON> <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> and <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON> at a courthouse ceremony in which the overflow crowd of about 300 sang `` The Battle Hymn of the Republic.'' The ceremony coincided with <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s state holiday for both Confederate Gen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> and King, who led the 1965 Selma-to-Montgomery voting rights march. The march took place with federal protection after a band of marchers were beaten and routed by mounted state troopers on the <LOCATION> Edmund </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pettus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>, which crosses the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION>. `` Bloody Sunday,'' as the bridge violence became known, drew national attention to the next march led by <PERSON> King </PERSON>, which helped inspire passage of the 1965 federal Voting Rights Act. `` I suspect there is no place on this planet that is more identified with Dr. <PERSON> King </PERSON> and his quest for <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> justice than right here in <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said after Monday's ceremony a few blocks from the bridge Turner investigated violence against voting rights marchers in 1965 and is acting head of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s civil rights division for the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. He and a team of <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers helped win the election system change in <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION>. `` I predict that someday students of modern history will point to <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, as 20th century <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s cradle of democracy, where people of all races began to live Doctor King's dream of brotherhood,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said.
