<HEAD>Case Of Four Jailed For IRA Pub Bombings Sent To Court Of Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to CORRECT Richardson's age to 31,
break up paragraphs, correct to four number sentenced. Picks up 7th pvs,
`In a ...' ^By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Citing new evidence, the government has reopened the case of four people jailed for life in two 1974 bombings of British pubs that killed seven people, including three soldiers, and injured 91. The bombings occurred during a wave of <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> terrorism, and champions of the `` <LOCATION> Guildford </LOCATION> Four'' said the government had in its zeal to obtain convictions ignored evidence that pointed to other suspects. The Irish government welcomed Monday's decision, and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> said in an editorial today that it was `` as difficult as it was wise.'' Responding to pressure that made the case a cause celebre in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, Home Secretary <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> told Parliament Monday that new information had emerged meriting that the case be heard by the Court of Appeal. <PERSON> Carole </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, 31; <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, 36; <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, 34, and <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Conlon </PERSON>, 33, were convicted of planting bombs in two pubs frequented by British soldiers in <LOCATION> Guildford </LOCATION>, a town southwest of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, in October 1974. Five people, including two soldiers, were killed and 65 injured. <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> also were convicted of a pub bombing in the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> suburb of <ORGANIZATION> Woolwich </ORGANIZATION> a month later in which the bartender and a soldier died and 26 people were injured. All four were sentenced to life imprisonment in October 1975, and two years later a court rejected their appeal. In a written reply to a lawmaker's question, <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said he was satisfied that `` there are new and substantial points which clearly ... are best considered by the court.'' These, he said, included apparent alibis for <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> that had never been put to a court, and indications that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> was injected with drugs during her interrogation and suffering symptoms of withdrawal from barbiturates. `` The possible effects of these drugs on the reliability of her statements were not adequately exposed to the jury or the Court of Appeal,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said. However, <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> declined to act on a point of law raised by two senior <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> judges who have argued that the appeals court ruled against the four despite being aware of confessions by two <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> men to the bombings. The Irish government, in a statement, said it `` has consistently conveyed the serious concern about the <LOCATION> Guildford </LOCATION> Four case to the British authorities.'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> McKee </PERSON>, co-author of `` Time Bomb,'' a recent book on the case, said: `` We are very gratified that this is the first official recognition of the justifiable concern about this case which has attracted people of the eminence of two archbishops, two Law Lords and two former Home Secretaries.'' The archbishops are Archbishop of Canterbury <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>, spiritual head of the Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Archbishop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardinal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Basil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hume </ORGANIZATION>, leader of Roman Catholics in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>. The Law Lords, two of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s most senior judges, are Lord <PERSON> Devlin </PERSON> and Lord Scarman. The two former Home Secretaries are <PERSON> Merlyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Rees </PERSON> and Lord <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>. Cardinal <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> O </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiaich </PERSON>, the Roman Catholic Primate of <LOCATION> All </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, called Monday's move a `` culmination of the efforts of people in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> who have become convinced of the innocence of these people.'' It is the second time in two years that the government has reopened a case involving people convicted of <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> terrorism who claimed to be victims of a miscarriage of justice. Six Irishmen serving life terms for pub bombings in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> in 1974 that killed 21 people went before the <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> after a similar campaign but their convictions were upheld last year. Like the <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> Six, the <LOCATION> Guildford </LOCATION> Four have figured strongly in Anglo-Irish relations. They are held up as examples by those who claim <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> courts are biased against the Irish or those who sympathize with the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>. The mainly <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> is fighting to end British rule in Protestant-dominated <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and unite it with the 95 percent <LOCATION> Catholic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> under socialist rule.
