<HEAD>State Trying To Break Into The Broadcast Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> it wo n't be, but a state official is hoping to start a little `` Voice of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>'' of sorts. And little it will be if <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Warnecke </PERSON> starts broadcasting governmental proceedings on 10 watts of power. That's roughly a five-mile radius from the transmitter. <PERSON> Warnecke </PERSON>, director of the Division of Telecommunications, wants the AM station to promote tourism in <LOCATION> Frankfort </LOCATION>. No disc jockeys have been chosen, and no decision has been made about whether Gov. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> will figure in the programming. However, a contract to build the transmitter will be put to bid later this month, and whoever gets the contract will have to apply for a licence from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on behalf of the state. <PERSON> Vicky </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Tourism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> said programming likely would include publicity about attractions in <LOCATION> Frankfort </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Motorists would be alerted to the broadcast by signs along the highway, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said. It's hoped the message would lure drivers into the capital city. The small coverage area would be similar to the low-power broadcasts that some major airports use to keep travelers aware of traffic conditions.
