<FIRST>r a PM-HumanRights     01-17 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Human Rights,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Human Rights Policies Criticized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two human rights organizations have chastised the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for providing military and financial assistance to military groups with poor human rights records. In particular, the organizations cited aid to the Contra rebels in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> insurgency in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, and the national armies of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, and the <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. The criticism was detailed in a report, `` The <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s Record on Human Rights in 1988,'' issued Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> New-York </ORGANIZATION> based organization that monitors and promotes human rights worldwide. The two groups praised the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for placing a greater emphasis on human rights during the last few years than it had earlier. The report noted the administration's insistence that human rights occupy a prominent place in the U.S.-Soviet agenda, which it said has led to improvements in human rights in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, including the release of hundreds of political and religious prisoners. While the report acknowledged that Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was also responsible for these changes, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration was credited with taking `` advantage of the <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> opening'' by placing `` consistent pressure on human rights issues.'' But the report chastised the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for largely disregarding `` rights transgressions in a host of friendly countries which attract little public attention in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, such as <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>.'' According to the report, `` human rights violations often were overlooked out of fear that criticizing an ally, particularly allied militaries fighting leftist rebellions, would create an opportunity for communist influence.'' For example, it said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was `` a vocal apologist for gross abuses'' in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> because the country is seen as a front-line state against the Soviet army. The report said the administration's `` most conspicuous failing'' was that it `` rarely protested abuses committed by the military once a civilian occupied a presidential palace ... Moreover, in certain cases, such as <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and occasionally the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, the administration minimized abuses or denied that they were taking place.'' The administration also was attacked for refraining from criticizing human rights violations by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> against Palestinians in occupied territories. But the report praised the administration for providing `` pressure at key moments to nudge certain dictators and military juntas allied with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> towards elections, as well as to protect newly elected civilian governments against military coups.'' For example, the report stated that in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, the administration played a role in `` easing out dictators and military juntas and replacing them with elected heads of state.'' It also praised <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, the report gave the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration credit for weighing `` in at key moments when restive militaries threatened to overwhelm newly elected civilian presidents.'' The report called on the incoming <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration `` to report human rights violations accurately and to speak out against serious abuses wherever they are found.'' Human Rights Watch includes the organizations <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Watch </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> Watch and <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> Watch. The <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is a public interest law center working to promote international human rights law and legal procedures in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and abroad.
</TEXT>
