<HEAD>Austrian Tourist Fined For Whale Harassment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Austrian tourist was fined $ 1,500 after pleading guilty to harassing whales off <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION>. `` It seems perfectly clear that he was chasing the whales,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> Daral </PERSON> <PERSON> Conklin </PERSON> said Monday in issuing the fine for <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottwald </PERSON>. `` Were he a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen, he would spend several nights in jail.'' In exchange for the guilty plea, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office dropped its request for a jail sentence. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bent </PERSON>, who attended the court session, said he was satisfied with the fine. Although federal offices and courts were closed in observance of Martin Luther King Day, the hearing was held so <PERSON> Gottwald </PERSON> could return to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> later in the day. <PERSON> Gottwald </PERSON> said he pleaded guilty in order to return home. `` This is ridiculous _ the whole situation,'' he said. `` This is not the aloha spirit.'' <PERSON> Gottwald </PERSON> and his girlfriend rented a boat on <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> on Jan. 3 and went to a protected area to get a good look at the whales. He says he did not think he was harassing the whales and was not sure how close he was allowed to get.
