<SECOND>PM-Boys Arrested,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Seeking Adult Who Hired Kids to Sell Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WYANDANCH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police are looking for an adult who may have been behind an alleged drug-selling venture by two boys, ages 10 and 14, who were arrested with $ 226 cash and three vials of crack in their pockets. The youngsters were charged Sunday with possession of a controlled substance, but the charges were reduced to juvenile delinquency because of their ages. They were to appear in <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Family Court today. The boys told police they had been working with an adult. They both had family court warrants against them on non-drug related juvenile delinquency charges. `` It's a crying shame,'' said <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Police Lt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynagh </PERSON>. `` These dealers are using whatever means they have to sell crack.'' The youngsters were nabbed in a popular drug-selling location in this city on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> where police periodically swoop in and arrest drug dealers, <PERSON> Lynagh </PERSON> said Monday. `` I was shocked ... When I saw them, I could not believe how old they were,'' said <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Police Patrolman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Castorf </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lynagh </PERSON> said police want to question the adult for whom the youths said they were working. The adult is apparently known to police but they declined to identify him. Three weeks ago, <PERSON> Lynagh </PERSON> said, another 10-year-old boy was arrested for selling drugs in the same area. In that case, an adult who had hired the youngster was later arrested, he said. `` These people believe we will not arrest the children, so they have them make the deals, `` <PERSON> Lynagh </PERSON> said. `` The kids are told to run when they see a cop.''
