<HEAD>Soviets Hand Out Rations As Food and Fuel Crises Worsen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government soldiers today pushed back with clubs and tree branches a crowd that thronged Soviet troops as they doled out emergency fuel rations in an impoverished section of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Less than a month before the scheduled <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> withdrawal, the besieged capital is plagued by severe food and fuel shortages. One woman was knocked to the ground as the crowd, ignoring repeated shouts from megaphone-toting Soviet soldiers to back away, surged around the three armored personnel vehicles distributing fuel in the <LOCATION> Khairkhana </LOCATION> section. People banged on empty gasoline cans as the Afghan soldiers shoved back the crowd. One soldier, a rifle under his arm, kicked and punched several teen-agers. Soviet troops, five aboard each armored car, looked uncomfortable as they poured gasoline for home heating into cans held up by people who waited in 19-degree temperatures at the front of the line. `` My children are cold, I've never seen conditions so bad,'' said one woman, who gave her name as <PERSON> Aziza </PERSON>, a 35-year-old with nine children. Another woman wailed as she held out her hands to a reporter and _ speaking through an interpreter _ pleaded for help, saying she and her children were hungry. Asked if she thought the reporter was a Soviet, she said, `` All I know is you are foreigners, perhaps you can help us.'' The Soviet unit used the megaphones to spread word of the emergency distribution as the armored vehicles, with 75mm cannons pointing skyward, rolled into <LOCATION> Khairkhana </LOCATION>. In other parts of the city, lines of several hundred cars and buses snaked around entire blocks waiting for fuel. Children joined bread lines outside shacks owned by private bread sellers, who get their dwindling wheat supplies from a state-run wheat silo. Western aid officials expressed growing alarm at the shortages. They are blamed on increasing disruption of Soviet-escorted supply convoys by anti-Marxist Moslem guerrillas attacking the key <LOCATION> Salang </LOCATION> highway, which runs north from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> to the Soviet border. First signs of the latest shortages came after more Soviet troops pulled out early this month, Western diplomats reported. The situation appears to have worsened considerably this week. Diplomats say Soviet troops are pulling out of the capital ahead of the Feb. 15 deadline set in a U.N.-mediated agreement. The withdrawal comes nearly a decade after <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> intervened to prop up a Marxist government. Under the agreement, 50,000 Soviet troops left by Aug. 15. The guerrillas, who have ignored calls for a cease-fire by President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, appear to be tightening an economic blockade of the capital and are viewed as increasingly effective as Afghan soldiers take over <LOCATION> Salang </LOCATION> road defenses from departing Soviet units. Officials of <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Children's Fund, today said the struggle for scarce food and fuel has cut attendance at its 40 mother and child welfare clinics in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> by nearly half. `` They say they ca n't come because they have to stand in bread and fuel queues,'' said <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> mission. In the fuel line in <LOCATION> Khairkhana </LOCATION>, an old, bearded man, his hands trembling as he clutched his empty gasoline can, said, `` Allah has brought this on us. We are black-faced in the sight of Allah.'' Others blamed the fighting or said the guerrillas were trying to cut off the capital. Some said they now do n't want the Soviets _ about whom Afghans in the street are usually openly hostile _ to leave.
