<HEAD>Court Rejects Challenge to Virginia Law on Child-Care Centers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected a challenge to a state law exempting religiously affiliated child-care centers from some health and safety standards all other child-care centers must meet. The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court ruling that the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law does not violate the constitutionally required separation of government and religion. The disputed 1979 state licensing law allows child-care centers run by churches or other religious organizations to seek an exempt status _ avoiding many of the health and safety standards applied to such facilities. Exempt centers still must meet basic health and safety standards, however. Child-care centers with no religious affiliation must obtain a state license, and are not entitled to seek the exemption. Among the 215 centers that could obtain exempt status under the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law, 106 have opted instead to operate with state licenses. The law was challenged in 1980 by three licensed child-care centers that have no religious ties _ <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Early </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Learning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lynchburg </LOCATION>, Academy Day Care in <LOCATION> Woodbridge </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Holloman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Grafton </LOCATION>. A federal judge struck down the exemption as unconstitutional but the 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reversed that ruling last May 6. `` Absent the exemption, some church leaders would immediately be forced to violate their convictions against submitting aspects of their ministries to state licensing, or face legal action,'' the appeals court said. Its ruling relied heavily on a 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision in which the justices said religious organizations may practice employment discrimination by favoring members of their faith even for non-religious jobs. In that case, the court unanimously upheld the firing in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> of a gymnasium custodian who failed to qualify for membership in the <ORGANIZATION> Mormon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, which owned and ran the gym. The court, in that 1987 ruling, said a 1972 federal law exempting religious groups from a federal anti-bias law does not violate separation of church and state. After the non-religious centers in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> appealed the 4th Circuit court's decision, state officials filed a counter-appeal contending that the appeals court was wrong in ruling that the centers had the proper `` standing'' to challenge the 1979 law. Today, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> denied review to both appeals. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Early </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Learning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 88-730, and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> Early Learning Center, 88-932.
