<HEAD>Court Sets Aside Ruling on Labor Unions in Missouri Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today set aside a ruling that limited the access enjoyed by labor unions that represent federal government employees to the home addresses of all their members. The justices told a federal appeals court to restudy its ruling that requires federal agencies to give employees an opportunity to have their addresses withheld from their union. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> decided in two cases that denying the unions access to the information is an unfair labor practice. But the 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> limited the authority's decision in a ruling last January. The appeals court said that although unions generally are entitled to the addresses, the information may not be disclosed without the employee's consent. In a brief order today, the justices set aside the 8th Circuit court's ruling and ordered the appeals court to restudy the two cases in light of regulations published by the two federal agencies involved. In one case, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> sought the names and home addresses of some 900 union members who work for the <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. In the second case, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <