<HEAD>Chinese Near Limit of Subsidized Wheat Purchases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Private exporters have sold an additional 200,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> at subsidized prices, almost cleaning out <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s current authorization under the program, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said today. <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>, general sales manager for the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the wheat was part of 1 million tons authorized Dec. 30 for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> under the Export Enhancement Program, or EEP Under the <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> arrangement, exporters can sell wheat and other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition. Exporters then collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or subsidies. The wheat sales were handled by two companies: <ORGANIZATION> Cargill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 115,000 tons, and <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dreyfus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 85,000 tons. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the wheat was sold for March shipment and will carry an average subsidy rate of $ 22.49 per ton, or about 62 cents per bushel. Only 10,000 tons remain available to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> under the program, he said. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat. The 200,000 tons of wheat would be about 7.34 million bushels. Wheat prices at the farm have been averaging around $ 4.09 per bushel, according to recent <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> market figures, making the new sale worth an estimated $ 30 million.
