<HEAD>Solidarity's Chronicle of Survival</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Key events in Solidarity history:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1980</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Aug. 14 _ Electrician <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> leads an occupation stike at <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>'s Lenin shipyard and starts a worker revolt against the communist state. Aug. 31 _ Legal registration makes Solidarity the Soviet bloc's only independent union During its 16 months of legal activity, Solidarity membership will grow to an estimated 10 million and a sense of renewal will sweep the nation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1981</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 13 _ Martial law is declared by Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, Solidarity activities are suppressed and thousands of members are interned, including <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1982</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Oct. 8 _ Solidarity is banned and an official trade union alliance is created to take its place. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> expands <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions against <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> by suspending its `` most favored'' trade status. Nov. 11 _ <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> is freed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1983</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 July 22 _ <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> lifts martial law but leaves many restrictive edicts. Oct. 5 _ <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> wins the Nobel Peace Prize. Oct. 3 _ The government steps up pressure on key activists still underground and offers 11 in prison, including advisers to <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, `` one-way passports'' out of the country to avoid trial on sedition charges.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1984</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 July 21 _ An amnesty is approved for political prisoners, including the 11 prominent union leaders jailed after the martial-law crackdown. Oct. 19 _ The popular pro-Solidarity priest, the Rev. <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Popieluszko </PERSON>, is slain. Four state security police will be tried and convicted in the murder.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1985</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Aug. 31 _ <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> accuses the government of presiding over a political, economic and cultural disaster as supporters nationwide mark the fifth anniversary of Solidarity's birth.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1986</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Sept. 11 _ The government orders the release of 225 political prisoners, including all senior Solidarity leaders.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Feb. 19 _ <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> lifts the last of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions against <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Nov. 29 _ Poles vote in first referendum in 41 years, but deny government support for economic reform package.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 April 24-May 10 _ Strikes hit steel mills, shipyards and other plants across <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Police break up one strike others gradually die out. Aug. 16 _ Workers declare a strike at the July Manifesto coal mine in <LOCATION> Jasztrebie </LOCATION> in a pay dispute. The strikes spread, creating <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s worst wave of labor strife in seven years. Aug. 26 _ Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> proposes talks with workers, laying the groundwork for a possible government meeting with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>. Aug. 31 _ On the eighth anniversary of the legalization of Solidarity, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> holds his first meeting with government officials in six years and appeals to workers to end strikes. Sept. 3 _ July Manifesto miners end their strike. Sept. 19 _ The government led by Prime Minister <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Messner </PERSON> resigns amid sharp criticism of its management of the economy. Sept. 27 _ <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> names <PERSON> Micezyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> as prime minister. Oct. 25 _ The talks are postponed as government objects to two opposition participants. Oct. 31 _ Government announces plans to close <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> shipyard in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> as unprofitable. Nov. 30 _ <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> holds an unprecedented live TV debate with <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Miodowicz </PERSON>, head of the official trade union. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> is hailed as the victor, and government polls show support for legalizing Solidarity on the rise. Dec. 20-21 _ At the first part of a party plenum, <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> members are instructed to poll the party rank-and-file for their attitude toward Solidarity.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Jan. 4 _ The government plans price increases of 20 percent and hopes to hold overall inflation to 50 percent. Jan. 13 _ A party source says the government is willing to restore Solidarity's legal status if it joins in political and economic reforms. Jan. 16 _ At the second part of a party plenum, <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> members debate whether <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s future includes trade union pluralism. Jan. 17 _ <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> urges the party to legalize Solidarity on condition it not be a government opponent that would `` pull the country into anarchy.''
