<HEAD>Baker Says US Should Aim to Keep Soviets on Constructive Track</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restructures top, picks up 5th graf pvs, ``Bipartisanship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State-designate <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> called today for a renewal of bipartisanship in foreign policy and a joint effort with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to ensure that `` a more responsible, constructive policy'' emerges from the changes reshaping the Soviet system. `` Yes, this is an appeal for a kinder, gentler <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said at a hearing by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on his nomination to take over the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> after President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> takes office. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> was the first of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s Cabinet choices to start then confirmation process. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> also said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can not abandon the Contra rebels opposing <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist Sandinista government. `` We must stand by them until our mutual goals are achieved,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said, adding that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must insist on protection for human rights not only in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> but in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and other Central American nations as well. He said the premier task of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy must be make certain that the Soviets move toward positive changes. `` Our task is to arrange affairs so that whatever the outcome of perestroika, a more responsible, constructive Soviet policy will remain in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s interest,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. Sketching a broad outline of the foreign policy goals of the incoming administration, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said experience has shown that a bipartisan foreign policy is an indispensable ingredient of success as the nation faces the problems and turmoil of an increasingly complex world. `` Bipartisanship does not mean that we must always agree,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` There are and always will be differences in approach and substance.'' `` But eventually we must proceed,'' he said. `` And when we do it is best that we do so together if we are to achieve the national interest.'' `` Yes, this is an appeal for a kinder, gentler <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` Bipartisanship ... is the lubricant that enables the branches of government to overcome their natural constitutionally designed friction, a friction that arises from our differences of perspectives and our different responsibilities.'' `` As a realist, I know we need bipartisanship to succeed,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` In order to succeed we must work together.'' The first order of business between the Republican administration and the Democratic-run <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, he suggested, is a `` meeting of our minds on how to proceed with a changing <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> suggested that if that happens, conclusions will include the need to modernize <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conventional and nuclear weapons, to set `` realistic and prudent standards'' for conventional arms control and to reach a common approach on the issue of loans and credits to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` Realism forces us to be prudent,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` However fascinating the twists and turns of perestroika -LRB- economic restructuring -RRB- may be and however riveting the details of decline as reported in Soviet newspapers, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> remains a heavily armed superpower.'' `` The talk is different but the force structure and policies that support far-reaching interests and clients have not changed commensurately,'' the nominee said. `` Many of those policies and those clients are hostile to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> values and threaten our interests. That's a reality.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> proposed a multi-step approach to Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s new policies, among them: _ Continue to welcome reform and changes _ Recognize that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policies and strength have contributed to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s new sense of realism _ Continue to probe the Soviets on arms control, human rights, regional conflicts and overall relations _ Place additional emphasis on ending regional conflicts in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and `` not allow the rhetoric of restraint to become a substituter for restraint itself. _ Seek help from the Soviets in dealing with such global problems as drugs, terrorism and the environment and if it is not forthcoming, find out why As the hearings opened, many senators were hoping to learn in what areas of foreign policy the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will differ from the often ideologically rigid positions pursued by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in the last eight years. But <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, a friend of the president-elect and pragmatic political ally of longstanding, may be hindered in his responses by his lack of direct foreign policy experience. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s former chief of staff and secretary of the treasury, did obtain experience dealing with the world's financial leaders during his years at the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s first term. He drew up the <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> plan to deal with Latin American debt. The plan calls for increased lending by commercial banks to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in return for economic restructuring. Some expect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who served as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> liaison officer to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and director of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, will seek to set his administration's foreign policy direction himself, leaving <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> to manage it. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> does, in fact, possess skill as a tactical policy manager and a clear ability to deal easily with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. While senators will seek to learn exactly what <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> will be asked to manage, some are dubious about obtaining concrete results, at least this early in the game. `` <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> will duck every substantive question,'' was the flat prediction of one <ORGANIZATION> Democrtic </ORGANIZATION> staff member who helped plan the two days of confirmation hearings and who asked not to be identified by name. Still, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is almost certain to confirm <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, possibly before the end of the month. But before it does, lawmakers will seek <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s public agreement to consult widely with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as events and policies unfold and to link hands in a search for a bipartisan foreign policy.
