<FIRST>r w AM-LatinDebt     01-17 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Latin Debt,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Calls For Debt Renegotiation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Latin American nations must negotiate debt reduction agreements with commercial bank creditors or face a worsening economic situation that could lead to the return of military dictatorships in the region, a panel of experts said Tuesday. The negotiation recommendation was made in a report by the Inter-American Dialogue, a grouping of 66 prominent citizens from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. Another key recommendation was for the incoming <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and leaders of other industrialized countries to actively encourage debt reduction agreements and to provide `` appropriate financial guarantees'' to support such initiatives. `` Six years after the debt crisis began, <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> remains mired in depression,'' the group said in its 59-page report. `` Unemployment and underemployment are at record levels,'' it said. `` Wages have declined sharply _ by as much as 50 percent in some places. Average income per capita has fallen back to the level of 1978 and is not recovering.'' The report, `` The <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> in 1989: Consensus for Action,'' said the alternative for <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to decisive action is a `` treadmill of austerity, stagnation and rising debt.'' It said the crisis could condemn <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> `` to a long period of economic hardship and political turbulence.'' `` In some countries, civilian authorities may be forced to yield to military rule,'' thus reversing a strong trend over the past decade toward elected government, it said. The report also recommended that: _ The nations of <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> revamp development strategies, restructure their economies and effectively integrate them in the world economy _ The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> address its own economic problems and join other industrial countries to reduce international financial imbalances, open world markets and sustain world growth _ The international financial institutions, including the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, sharply step up lending to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, provided the debtor governments adhere to economic reform programs The co-chairmen of the report panel were <PERSON> Sol </PERSON> <PERSON> Linowitz </PERSON>, a former ambassador to the Organization of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and a negotiator of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> treaties; and former Costa Rican President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Oduber </PERSON>. Also on the ideologically diverse panel were former presidents <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ardito </PERSON> <PERSON> Barletta </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Osvaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> and numerous former cabinet ministers from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The report listed the hemisphere's major debtors as <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. They account for 85 percent of the region's debt. Since 1985, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy on <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s foreign debt has been guided by the so-called <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> plan, named for former treasury secretary and now secretary of state-designate <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. The plan calls for increased lending by commercial banks to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in return for economic restructuring but lending levels since 1985 have been far below expectations. A month ago, President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> indicated he will undertake a major review of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy toward Third World debt because of the `` enormous problems'' facing <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. On <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the report called on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to end its diplomatic boycott of the Sandinista government and bilaterally negotiate mutual security arrangements. Saying `` there can be no double standard,'' the report also argued that <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> must `` desist from assisting insurgencies in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and elsewhere.'' On drug trafficking, the report said that action to reduce demand for narcotics `` must be given overriding emphasis'' in the struggle against drugs. `` As long as there is a demand for illicit drugs, supplies will find their way to it,'' the report said.
