<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInventories     01-17 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business Inventories, Sales Up 0.4 Percent in November</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business inventories rose 0.4 percent in November and sales rose at the same pace, the government said Tuesday in a report that analysts said bodes well for the nation's economy in the new year The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said inventories held on shelves and backlots rose to a seasonally adjusted $ 753.6 billion in November, while sales reached $ 503.8 billion. The matching 0.4 percent gains kept the ratio of inventories to sales at 1.50, meaning it would take 1.5 months to exhaust inventories at the November sales pace. When not accompanied by increasing sales, rising inventories can signal economic weakness because they may lead manufacturers to order production cuts and layoffs while they sell off reserve goods. But <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagens </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> WEFA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said the new report indicates that `` at least from the inventories point of view, we think the economy is in pretty good shape for continued growth in 1989.'' `` Oftentimes, before a recession, inventories tend to build up,'' he said. `` There's no evidence of any kind of excesses in inventories in the economy.'' The November increase in inventories followed a minuscule rise during October and a 0.9 percent jump in September. It was the 23rd straight month in which inventories had risen, but sales generally have kept pace. `` It looks like inventories closed out the year on a very lean note, which should be a positive sign in terms of growth in the first half of this year,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, a forecaster in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` People remained somewhat skeptical about the durability of the recovery. They kept their inventories rather lean.'' The monthly increase in sales was down from a 1.3 percent increase in October and virtually unchanged sales activity in September. The November sales gain was led by a 0.9 percent rise at the retail level, followed by a 0.5 percent increase at the manufacturing level. These two gains offset a 0.4 percent decline in sales at the wholesale level. The government last week reported that retail sales in December rose a lackluster 0.2 percent. The increase in inventories was led by a 0.7 percent rise in retailers' inventories, followed by a 0.4 percent increase for manufacturers and virtually no change in wholesale stockpiles.
</TEXT>
