had a stop sign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDINBURG, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, the father of Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, was killed in a traffic accident near this south <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> town this morning, police said. He was 92. The senior <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was killed when his car collided with another car at a rural intersection between <LOCATION> Edinburg </LOCATION> and Mission, a neighboring town just north of the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> border, said police Chief <PERSON> A.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzales </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s ranch, the <LOCATION> Arrowhead </LOCATION>, is about 30 miles northwest of the intersection. Two people in the second car were injured, neither critically. According to <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION>, the accident occurred when <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> failed to yield the right of way at the intersection. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> had a stop sign; the other car did not, <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> said. `` I do not know if he stopped and then pulled out in front of this oncoming vehicle or did n't stop,'' <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was pronounced dead at the scene by <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> of the Peace <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosel </PERSON>. The occupants of the second car were identified as driver <PERSON> Ramiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosales </PERSON> and his sister, <PERSON> Margarita </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosales </PERSON>. Both taken to <LOCATION> Mission </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>, where Ms. <PERSON> Rosales </PERSON> was listed in stable condition pending surgery; her brother was scheduled to be released after treatment for cuts and bruises. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> managed about 42,000 acres of farms and six ranches scattered over a south <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> empire he started carving out of the brush and thorn forest in 1920. He and his wife <PERSON> Dolly </PERSON>, who died in 1977, had three other children: <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> architect; <PERSON> Don </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION> businessman; and <PERSON> Betty </PERSON>, the wife of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Winn </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> won re-election to his <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat last November, when he also lost a run for vice president on the Democratic ticket with <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. His office in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> declined to comment on reports of the death.
