<HEAD>Ethnic Kurds Detained in Southeastern Turkey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Security officials have detained at least 200 people in the southeast in the past two weeks on charges of collaborating with Kurdish guerrillas, officials said Tuesday. <PERSON> Fuat </PERSON> <PERSON> Atalay </PERSON>, a deputy from the main opposition <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Populist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that more than 200 people of Kurdish origin had been detained in the province of <LOCATION> Diyarbakir </LOCATION>. Other sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said about 200 others were rounded up in nearby <LOCATION> Siirt </LOCATION> province. Kurdish guerrillas operating in the southeast are affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> Kurdish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which seeks to establish a Marxist state in parts of southeastern and eastern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. About 800 civilians and military personnel and an equal number of Kurdish rebels have been killed since the party began attacking military targets and villages in 1984. Ethnic Kurds make up about one-fifth of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s population of 55 million.
