<ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily, said many high-ranking Armenian officials had fueled the strife by their indecisiveness, and implied they might have been involved in the annexation movement itself. In all 68 persons received rebukes from the Armenian party's Politburo, Pravda said In addition, 13 executives were expelled from party ranks, and 36 officials in the party, government, police and economic management were fired, Pravda said. The Armenian Politburo charged the officials with destabilizing the situation in the southern <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and kindling nationalist dissension through indecisiveness, passivity, and negligence, Pravda said. The paper also reported officials had violated citizens' constitutional rights by resorting to threats and blackmail It did not specify what acts had occurred. The Armenian Politburo singled out two local party bosses for negligence and the absence of political leadership that it said caused deaths and massive emigration of the <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> population. The bureau recommended official rebukes for <PERSON> Y. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chshmarityan </PERSON> of the Stepanavansk region and <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ananyan </PERSON> of the Idzhevansk region. According to Pravda, the bureau also recommended Armenian Education Minister <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akhumyan </PERSON> be rebuked for not maintaining order in university classrooms. The Armenian Politburo also charged party officials with the task of penalizing communists `` who indulge in the estrangement of people by nationality, who allow extremist attacks or stir up nationalist hostilities.''
