<HEAD>The Capital Glows, but Not All of the City Within</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inauguration Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's capital will be trying to cover a ragged image with its Sunday best when the nation turns its eyes this way for the inauguration of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Police spokesman Lt. <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said officers would be working to keep the streets clear of crime and vice while <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is full of visitors celebrating the installation of a new president. `` We're going to intensify our efforts to abate many of the nuisances throughout the city,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, specifically mentioning increased efforts against prostitution and drug sales. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s facade, with its historic monuments and powerful residents, has cracked lately. The festivities come at a time when the city is dismayed by its murder rate _ 371 slayings last year, mostly due to drug wars _ and embarrassed by its mayor, <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, the subject of two investigations recently into his social ties with people who were the subjects of drug probes. `` Much has been said about the mayor and the city's image,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON>, the new president of the <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, said recently. `` Obviously, in the short term, this does n't help -LRB- business in the district -RRB-.'' The federal government has provided the <ORGANIZATION> D.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inaugural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> with $ 2.3 million to pay for police and fire protection, medical and ambulance service, traffic control, supervision of construction of stands along the parade route, food inspection and issuance of `` official inaugural maps,'' according to <PERSON> Cecilia </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> of the Office of Emergency Preparedness. Ms. <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said the city had made no plans to shove its homeless residents out of sight. Estimates of their numbers run from 7,500 to twice that figure. `` There's nothing that can be done,'' she said. `` It -LRB- homelessness -RRB- is a problem in the city. They have a right to watch the parade just like everyone else.'' But homeless-rights activist <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Non-Violence </ORGANIZATION> operates a shelter three blocks from the inaugural parade route, said police usually force the homeless out of sight by threatening to drive them far from town and leave them there. `` It happened to me in 1980,'' <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> said. `` I was homeless. Police came by about 5:30 in the morning and said, ` If you're not off this grate within half an hour, we'll take you somewhere and drop you off.' Most people realize what the police want. They want you to drop from sight. So you do.'' `` It's fairly common for homeless people to be hassled by police and by other officials on the street, told to move on, told that they're loitering, told that they are not to be there,'' said <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Foscarinis </PERSON>, counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> for the Homeless. `` It's not an unusual experience for homeless people. And what happens around times like inauguration is that those kinds of methods are greatly stepped up.'' At inauguration time in January 1985, image issues took a back seat to the homeless population's welfare because the district was locked in a dangerous cold wave. City police denied any role in moving homeless people this year. About a dozen people, many of them homeless, demonstrate daily in <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> across from the White House. Most of that park will be used for media coverage of the inaugural events, according to <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>, but a section has been set aside for protesters. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said homelessness is n't a problem on the Capitol grounds, which encompass 180 acres of parks and congressional office buildings `` It's against the law to sleep in the Capitol grounds outdoors,'' <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said, `` and homeless people are aware of that.''
