<HEAD>Court Urged to Broaden States' Child-Porn Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> was urged Tuesday to give states sweeping power to control child pornography by upholding a ban on nude depictions of children, even by a parent. `` It's clear that posing a child in a state of nudity can and does do harm,'' said Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. `` The child will experience shame, a fear of blackmail.'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> appealed to the justices to reverse a <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that threw out a state anti-pornography law on grounds it could make it a crime for parents to photograph their naked toddlers on the beach. Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, picking up on that theme, asked <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> what is wrong with taking a picture of a naked infant on a bear rug _ a pose familiar to millions. `` Those pictures are lawful,'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> replied. He said no prosecutor in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> ever envisioned invoking the invalidated law to prevent that sort of activity. Some justices suggested they could dispose of the case without issuing a broad ruling, dealing with the constitutionality of the law, because <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> has replaced the statute with a narrower law. The former law, enacted in 1982, made it a crime to encourage or permit a child under 18 `` to pose or be exhibited in a state of nudity'' for purposes of a photograph, picture or other `` visual reproduction,'' even for private, non-commercial use. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Legislature has since revised the law to make such activity illegal only if done with `` lascivious intent.'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said the new law might not be strong enough to protect children from sexual abuse. `` I can think of no obligation of the state that is more important,'' he said. He also said that while many states have laws against child pornography, he believed only <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> had passed statutes as tough as the one struck down in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> court ruling overturned the conviction of <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON>, 40, of <PERSON> Holden </PERSON> for taking photographs in 1984 of his 14-year-old stepdaughter while she posed topless, clad only in a red scarf and bikini underwear on a bar in their home. Prosecutors said the girl later threw the photos in the woods and <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> made her retrieve them. <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> was arrested after the girl's mother went to police with the photos He was sentenced to 10 years in prison and was paroled after two years. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> high court, by a 4-3 vote, said the law was too broad in restraining freedom of expression because it could make it a crime for a parent to take a snapshot of a `` naked one-year-old running on a beach or romping in a wading pool.'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vita </PERSON>, <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON>' lawyer, said Tuesday the state has not offered `` proof of serious harm to minors'' from posing in the nude. He said that the photographs at issue in the case are not pornographic and that the state was trying to outlaw `` an area of expression that is much a part of our culture.'' Some justices said the state does not have to prove harm to minors to outlaw such depictions. Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> questioned whether freedom of expression was at stake at all when a state makes it a crime to photograph someone in the nude. `` I do n't think you're talking about the First Amendment'' even when one says parents should be free to photograph their naked infants on a bear rug, <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> said. `` That's a question of whether the state can intrude on the parent-child relationship.'' The case is <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON>, 87-1651.
