<HEAD>With AM-East-West Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Czechoslovak police drove crowds from <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s main square with water cannons for a third day Tuesday, although no protest was being held, and 14 activists may be prosecuted, dissidents and witnesses said. Fourteen dissidents were detained Monday, including playwright <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, whose works are banned. They had tried to lay flowers in <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> to honor <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Palach </PERSON>, a 20-year-old student who burned himself alive 20 years ago to protest the Soviet-led invasion that ended the liberal `` Prague Spring'' in August 1968. A prosecutor told relatives <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemcova </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the human rights group Charter 77, and <PERSON> Sasha </PERSON> <PERSON> Vondra </PERSON>, a Charter 77 spokesman, would stay in custody for an unspecified period, a dissident source said by telephone phone from <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Nemcova </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> David </PERSON>, who was married Saturday, also was among the 14 arrested Monday along with <PERSON> Jana </PERSON> <PERSON> Sternova </PERSON>, a former Charter 77 spokeswoman who met with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> last year in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Emigre sources said privately that <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemcova </PERSON>'s wife <PERSON> Michaela </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vondra </PERSON>'s wife <PERSON> Martina </PERSON> were told their relatives would be charged under Article 156, Section A, of the criminal code, on obstructing the duty of a public official. The maximum jail sentence on conviction is six months. Whether charges would be pressed against any or all of the 14 was not clear, the informants said. Witnesses said police had at least four water cannons Tuesday and sprayed people in the square indiscriminately. About two dozen vans of police rushed into the square in what appeared to be a preventive measure, since no demonstration was being conducted. Except for several hundred young people, most of those in the square appeared to be people passing through on normal daily business, the witnesses said. The witnesses, speaking by telephone from <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, said people ran from the square to keep from being drenched and it was quiet after about two hours, with police patrolling constantly. CTK, the official Czechoslovak news agency, said 91 people were detained Sunday at a rally of at least 5,000 people in <PERSON> Palach </PERSON>'s honor An emigre source said 89 were released later Sunday, but a dissident source in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> quoted one of those freed as saying the number detained appeared to be much higher than reported by the agency. No official comment was available on the numbers of people arrested or released. The home telephone of government spokesman <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Pavel </PERSON> was not answered Tuesday. An <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter saw police beat several people at the Sunday rally. At least one man was so badly hurt that other demonstrators called for an ambulance. Several ambulances were seen rushing through the streets of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> on Sunday. <PERSON> Palach </PERSON> <PERSON> Press </PERSON>, an emigre publishing house in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, said a 59-year-old suffered a skull fracture. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kavan </PERSON> of <PERSON> Palach </PERSON> <PERSON> Press </PERSON> said it was not clear from his source whether the injury occurred Sunday or Monday, or whether the man was a demonstrator or bystander. Also among the 14 is <PERSON> Jana </PERSON> <PERSON> Sternova </PERSON>, a former Charter 77 spokeswoman who met with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> last year in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. After police cleared Wenceslas Square on Monday with tear ga