<SECOND>AM-China-Grain,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peasants Risk Lives Racing Trucks of Grain Across Province Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of peasants are running truckloads of grain across a provincial border in east <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> at breakneck speed in the dead of night to get top prices, a state newspaper said Tuesday. The Peasants Daily said in a front-page story that grain-running across <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION> provincial border into more prosperous neighboring provinces is dangerous but profitable because of low prices inside <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION>. Officials in the border region have tried to prevent the grain outflow by setting up checkpoints to stop trucks. But the paper said most trucks barrel past the checkpoints and elude pursuers in chases that have resulted in at least one death. The paper criticized <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION>'s low grain prices and its checkpoints and warned such policies would only dampen peasants' enthusiasm for planting grain at a time when grain harvests already are falling behind population growth. In one accident along what it called the `` blood-stained grain road,'' a 19-year-old youth driving a grain-laden truck lost control and crashed as he tried to speed past one checkpoint. He was killed. A few days earlier, a checkpoint official who chased a speeding truck leaped onto its running board and punched his fist through the window to force the driver to stop. The driver did not stop, but the official suffered cuts and had to undergo surgery, the paper said. `` The grain truckers who make these death-defying dashes are lured by the high prices'' outside <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION>, it wrote. `` After a three-mile dash, they can earn more than $ 270 for their load, but if they are stopped at the checkpoint they are fined $ 810. Who would n't risk his life? Peasants must sell a fixed portion of their harvests directly to the state but supppsedly are allowed to sell the rest on the open market in any province. Officials in <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION>, however, feared all the grain would flow to neighboring <LOCATION> Jiangsu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fujian </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION>, where higher prices are offered. The going price in <LOCATION> Jiangsu </LOCATION> after the autumn harvest was 12 cents a pound of unhusked rice, compared with 9.6 cents a pound in <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION> border area. The relatively wealthy provinces of <LOCATION> Fujian </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> to the southeast offer even more, the paper said. Both provinces have prosperous industrial and export sectors and generally attract much of the region's grain because of the high prices they can offer. Unhappy with <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION>'s low prices, many peasants have withheld from sale an estimated 300,000 tons of grain. The paper noted this means they will have less ready cash for investing in next year's crop. It did not comment on the impact on grain supplies, which are short in many parts of the country because of a poor harvest. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> harvested less than 393 million tons of rice, wheat and other grains in 1988, down from nearly 403 million tons in 1987.
</TEXT>
