<HEAD>Department Will Reserve Summer Jobs for Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that for the first time it will reserve some of its summer jobs for students from 17 historically black universities. Deputy Secretary <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said 563 of the 1989 summer jobs will be held aside as part of the department's effort `` to increase the number of minorty students in agriculture, forestry and home economics'' and to seek careers in those fields. Last year 17,753 students nationwide worked during the summer months for various <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agencies, and officials said they expect about that many this year. The 563 jobs reserved for the black schools would represent about 3 percent of the total. `` Agriculture is more than crop and livestock production,'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said. `` Animal and plant sciences, economics, forestry, marketing and computer technology are just some of the varied career fields in agriculture today.'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said the jobs will be with 19 <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agencies and will be located nationwide. He said interested students at 17 institutions should contact unversity placement offices before March 1. The universities, collectively known as 1890 institutions because of land-grant legislation that year, are being targeted in other ways by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said. On Dec. 29, the department announced it was establishing offices at each of the 17 schools to help encourage more minorities in agriculture. Also, on Jan. 9, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration proposed a <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> budget for next year that included $ 80.2 million for new and expanded programs to increase the teaching, recruitment and research capabilities at the 1890 schools, a 20 percent increase from the current level. The 17 schools are: <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>