<HEAD>Actor Trey Wilson Dies At Age 40</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Trey </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, a character actor who appeared on stage and screen in recent hits from `` Raising Arizona'' to `` <PERSON> Bull </PERSON> <PERSON> Durham </PERSON>,'' has died of a cerebral hemorrhage. He was 40. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION>, died Monday at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Massetti </PERSON>, spokeswoman for his manager, said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> was at home in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Sunday when he complained of a headache, and then lost consciousness. He was about to depart for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> to play a role that was written especially for him in `` <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s Crossing,'' a new film by <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ethan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coen </PERSON>, the brothers responsible for `` Raising <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>.'' In that film, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> played <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Arizona </PERSON>, the father of quintuplets, one of whom is stolen by a childless couple. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> also played the manager in `` Bull Durham''; an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> boss in `` Married to the Mob'; a wealthy Texan in `` Twins.'' He also appeared in `` A Soldier's Story,'' `` F-X'' and `` The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Carroll </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>.'' Two other films _ `` Welcome Home'' and `` Miss Firecracker'' _ have not yet been released, along with the just-completed `` Great Balls of Fire,'' the <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> story in which <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> plays <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>. He also appeared on stage in `` The Front Page'' at <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, `` Custom of the Country'' at the Second Stage and `` The Debutante Ball'' at <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. His Broadway credits include `` <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Pan </PERSON>,'' `` Tintypes,'' `` The First'' and `` Foxfire.'' He is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Blye </PERSON>; a stepson, <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Meadows </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; his mother, <PERSON> Mitzie </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>; and his stepfather, W.F. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, both of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. Burial was scheduled for Saturday in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. A memorial service would be held later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Massetti </PERSON> said.
