<SECOND>AM-China-Fresco,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cave Paintings Stolen From Famous Buddhist Shrine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thieves cut a 700-year-old fresco from the wall of one of northwestern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s famous <LOCATION> Dunhuang </LOCATION> caves, one-time <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> shrines filled with magnificent paintings and statues, the People's Daily reported Tuesday The theft, from a cave that was not open to the public, was discovered Friday, the paper said. The thieves cut the 10-square-foot fresco into five pieces for easy removal, but one piece broke, the report said. The report did not describe the painting or comment on how the thieves got into the cave. It said a fresco also was stolen from <LOCATION> Dunhuang </LOCATION> in 1986 and the thieves have not been found. In the fourth century, monks who first introduced Buddhism to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> opened cave temples in <LOCATION> Dunhuang </LOCATION>, along ancient trading routes in what is now <LOCATION> Gansu </LOCATION> province. Over the next few centuries, hundreds of caves were dug out of the arid hillsides of <LOCATION> Dunhuang </LOCATION> and their walls covered with religious murals. When the trade routes fell into disuse, the caves were abandoned and forgotten. They were rediscovered in about 1900 and found to contain thousands of priceless manuscripts and terra cotta statues. Only a few dozen of the caves are open to the public now as a tourist attraction. Millions of dollars' worth of ancient artifacts are smuggled out of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> each year, officials estimate, most through <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>.
