<HEAD>Shultz Chides East Europeans on Human Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> criticized four East European nations Tuesday about human rights and said `` dark areas remain'' in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but an aide reported Kremlin assurances of improvement. A senior <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said a ranking member of the Soviet delegation to the 35-nation <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> review conference told him during <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s last mission abroad `` the whole process will move ahead'' during the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. According to the official, speaking on condition of anonymity, the Soviet delegate said the cases of 20 more Jews who want to emigrate have been resolved and relatives of citizens who apply for exit visas no longer will be urged to object. Family objections have been used by Soviet authorities to reject applications. `` I really believe them,'' the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said. `` All these things are being volunteered.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> praised the Soviets and two East European allies, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, for taking steps to implement the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> agreements on European security and cooperation. He called Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> `` strong and creative,'' and credited him with improving human rights. Signed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and all European nations except <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> agreemenrference late last year. At a news conference, he called for the destruction of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall, built in 1961 to keep East Germans from fleeing to the West. `` There has been tremendous progress but the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall remains, as a symbol of the division of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, an inhumane structure and something that functionally separates people,'' he said. `` So, in the end that sort of thing has to come down.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> criticized <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> for reserving the right to select which provisions of Sunday's declaration it would observe, although he had not done so in his address. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> told delegates Sunday, before adoption of the final document, that it would not honor provisions on greater religious freedom and emigration. One provision of the document is a mandate for new negotiations, scheduled to begin March 9, on reducing conventional military forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` I have some genuine optimism about the prospects,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. His last trip as secretary of state was one of the shortest. He was in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> for 32 hours, then flew home to prepare to relinquish his office Friday.
