<HEAD>Law To Be Revised To Ensure Security Agency's Political Neutrality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A revised law will prevent the main government intelligence agency from engaging in political activity, the agency's chief said Tuesday. Park Seh-jik, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee the government would add a clause to the law governing the agency that would ban political activity. But he rejected an opposition demand that the agency's activity be limited to gathering information on <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and other foreign countries. `` In our reality, it is difficult to separate domestic intelligence from that on <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>,'' he said. The Agency for National Security, formerly the <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, has been a target of public criticism for its active involvement in politics. Political neutrality for the agency was a campaign pledge of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo in the December 1987 elections.
