<HEAD>Police Chase Armed Teen Through High School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police chased a 16-year-old boy armed with a pistol through the halls and across the roof of a high school Tuesday after the boy fired two shots at school employees, authorities said. `` There were no injuries and no shots were fired in the school,'' Officer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryson </PERSON> said. A security guard at <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> noticed the boy, armed with a .38 - caliber handgun, in the school at noon, school spokeswoman <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Parent </PERSON> The guard and Assistant Principal <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> chased the boy from the school and into Bayou St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> across the street, she said. When cornered in the bayou, Parent said the boy drew a gun and fired at <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and the security guard. Police joined school security in chasing the teen-ager, who ran back into school and through the halls with the gun, <PERSON> Bryson </PERSON> said. At one point, <PERSON> Bryson </PERSON> said, the boy pointed the weapon at a police sergeant who also had his weapon drawn. `` The sergeant ordered him to drop it, but he ran away instead,'' <PERSON> Bryson </PERSON> said. The boy climbed through a vent and onto the top of the three-story building, running back and forth across the roof before climbing down and being cornered outside the gymnasium, <PERSON> Bryson </PERSON> said. `` Police ordered him to drop the weapon that was pointed at several officers. After about 10 seconds he did so,'' <PERSON> Bryson </PERSON> said. The boy, who was not identified by name, is a student at another school, and police said they did not know why he was at <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION>. The boy was booked on several counts including attempted murder, <PERSON> Bryson </PERSON> said. Parent said students were kept in their rooms during the incident and classes continued.
