<HEAD>US, Soviets Try to Settle on Old Russian Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators have begun trying to settle the 70-year-old question of much <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> should pay for bonds issued by <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>'s last czarist government. Until now, the Soviet governments of <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> and his successors have refused to pay anything for the bonds, which had a value of $ 193 million when they were issued before 1919. Since then, unpaid interest has increased the total value of the bonds to $ 862 million, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The bonds were issued by the czarist government, but the last czar, <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, was overthrown and shot in the 1917 revolution. <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>'s government repudiated them two years later. Since then, the bonds were considered to have little or no value, and were often valued more for the beauty of their engraving than any hope they would be repaid. <ORGANIZATION> Carl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, owns bonds with a face value of $ 20 million. But <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Claster </PERSON>, its chief operating officer, says there is no market for them. `` You make a market,'' he told an interviewer. `` How much will you give me? Five cents on $ 100?'' Negotiations began in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet diplomats in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Nov. 28 and the two sides agreed to hold another meeting, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. But <PERSON> Nyoka </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, public affairs office for the department's <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> and Canadian Affairs, said she did not know when or where it will take place. The Soviets have already made deals with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> on czarist bonds held by citizens of those nations. Making a deal with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> might make it easier to float new Soviet bonds here, though Ms. <PERSON> White </PERSON> said there would be several legal obstacles. One of those hurdles may be another $ 674 million the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> still carries on its books from World War II, which is part of the $ 9 billion cost of food and equipment sent to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under the `` lend-lease'' plan of World War II. In addition, the Soviets also owe $ 109 million to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Export-Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, although the Soviets are keeping current on those payments. Many European banks have opened new lines of credit for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, and some American banks, including the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, are interested in doing more business. These deals, which according to some estimates now reach $ 7 billion, evoked criticism from former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON>, who called them a potential aid to the Soviet military. `` These may be all going into production of better fertilizer,'' he said in a speech to business executives last month. `` The same chemicals, however, are used for chemical warfare in many cases.'' But <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Zehnder </PERSON>, press relations officer for the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, said a distinction should be made between short-term loans for trade deals and longer-term lines of credit such as those being offered by banks in western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He said his bank is interested only in short-term deals. `` These are n't for missiles that are going to be used to bomb <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' he said in a telephone interview from his <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> office. First <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> has agreed with a Soviet bank in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naordny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, to finance projects in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other east European countries. <PERSON> Zehnder </PERSON> says it plans to introduce the Soviet bank to its clients who want to do business in the East.
