<HEAD>Official Newspaper Says Leadership Can't Control Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A deeply divided communist leadership is unable to control the country's economic and political crisis, and further social upheaval is imminent, a state-run newspaper said Tuesday. `` The following is clear: this country is not being run by anyone,'' the leading official daily <ORGANIZATION> Borba </ORGANIZATION> said in an editorial. `` More precisely, it is being run by divided, dangerously antagonistic <ORGANIZATION> republican </ORGANIZATION> leaderships with different ideological concepts, creating chaos in politics and economy,'' <ORGANIZATION> Borba </ORGANIZATION> said. Meanwhile, the ruling 23-member Politburo announced that on Jan. 25 the policy-setting <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> will `` discuss the political situation in the country, relations within the party and the functioning and responsibility of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and its Politburo.'' The wording of the announcement, carried by the state <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency, indicated the session might result in leadership changes. In an apparent attempt to bridge the growing rifts between <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s republics, the nine-member state presidency on Tuesday appealed to opposing leaderships `` to settle their differences by dialogue.'' Public discontent after years of rising inflation and falling living standards, <ORGANIZATION> Borba </ORGANIZATION> said, `` is turning into a full-scale revolt,'' threatening the very foundations of the communist system. `` The crisis is so deep that it can, at any moment, cause even greater social upheavals, which would force the country into a completely unwanted direction,'' the paper said. The most liberal republics of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> favor political pluralism and more democracy as a solution to the country's woes, but southern regions led by the country's largest republic of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> advocate more central control and a greater role for the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The choice of a new premier later this week may cause yet another sharp clash between the country's liberal and conservative regions. <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said the worsening crisis calls for an emergency party congress meeting to resolve conflicts and elect a completly new leadership. `` It is better to have an extraordinary congress than to be forced to introduce extraordinary measures,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said. The country's six republics and two provinces have wide autonomy in political and economic affairs, creating eight virtually self-ruling states that must reach consensus when passing important new laws. That often leads to watered-down compromises. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is faced with confusion sometimes bordering on `` political chaos,'' <ORGANIZATION> Borba </ORGANIZATION> said. Unable to control the economic crisis, the federal <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> resigned last month, leaving the country virtually ungoverned, the <ORGANIZATION> Vecernje </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Novosti </ORGANIZATION> daily said. In addition, under pressure from hard-line <ORGANIZATION> Serbian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Serbian </LOCATION> leaders, the party elites in the provinces of <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> and in the republic of <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION> have been ousted and only interim leaderships have been left in charge of the regions. The ouster of the entire <LOCATION> Montenegrin </LOCATION> ruling elite came after more than 120,000 people demonstrated last week in <LOCATION> Titograd </LOCATION>, the region's capital, demanding the leadership step down because of the disastrous state of the republic's economy The action was applauded by <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s state-controlled media. But the mass demonstrations in <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION> were denounced in the liberal northern republics of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> and described as being covertly `` orchestrated'' by followers of <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, who is alleged to have federal leadership ambitions.
