<FIRST>r w AM-Mayors-Homeless     01-17 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mayors-Homeless,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayors Say Homelessness Increasing, Especially Among Families</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Urban homelessness and hunger increased significantly in 1988, particularly among families with children, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday in reporting results of a survey of 27 major cities. One of every four homeless persons in the surveyed cities was a child. `` Families _ women and children _ they make up the most significant increase we have experienced,'' <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said in releasing the findings. The conference, which conducts an annual survey of hunger and homelessness, reported that both had risen in nearly all of the cities it surveyed. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, D-Tenn., speaking to the mayors later, called the survey `` a devastating indictment of the neglect of the needs of our major urban centers. He said the mayors had made a compelling case for increased spending on the problems. <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said the rate of increase seemed to have slowed a bit from the previous year, in part because of increased emergency services provided by state and local governments. Officials in every city surveyed cited a lack of affordable housing as the main cause of homelessness, and <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> blamed a sharp decline in federal spending on low-income housing during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> admininistration. `` Shelters are not the answer,'' <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said. `` Permanent, affordable housing _ that is the answer.'' The survey was released at the opening of the annual winter meeting of the organization of big-city mayors. The survey was conducted among the 27 cities whose mayors sit on the conference's <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on Hunger and Homelessness, headed by <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> Among its findings were that in the past year in the surveyed cities: _ Requests for emergency shelter increased an average 13 percent. All but two of the cities registered an increase. _ Requests for emergency food were up an average 19 percent. Three-fifths of those asking for emergency food were memebers of families. _ An average of 19 percent of the requests for emergency shelter went unmet; and among homeless families the figure was 23 percent. Shelters in two out of three cities reported they turned away homeless families because of a lack of resources. _ In 62 percent of the cities, emergency food assistance facilities had to turn away people, also for lack of resources. _ On average the composition of the homeless population was 49 percent single men, 34 percent members of families, 13 percent single women and the rest unaccompanied youth. One in four was a child. An average 34 percent of homeless were substance abusers and one-fourth were severely mentally ill; 23 percent had full-time or part-time jobs; 26 percent were veterans. <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> called for more federal spending on urban problems, and said he was encouraged by President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s stated commitment to making homelessness a high priority. The <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> mayor said that by holding the increase in the defense budget to the inflation rate in the coming fiscal year, an extra $ 4 billion could be made avilable for low-income housing and emergency shelter programs. That would not solve the problem, he said, but could at least pay for emergency shelter programs and get started on increasing the availability of affordable housing. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s choice for secretary of housing and urban development, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, is to meet with the mayors Wednesday. The survey was conducted among officials from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, P.R.; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>.; <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>.
