chev </PERSON>. `` My personal viewpoint is that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is in a much stronger position than -LRB- seen by -RRB- the conventional wisdom in this country,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` I think there are a lot of skeptics in this country about him. I think he's in a very strong position. `` He's consolidated power much quicker than any other Soviet general secretary. He's way ahead of -LRB- the late Leonid -RRB- <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. He -LRB- <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> -RRB- consolidated power in three years which took <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> 10 years to do.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he had not met <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> but considers him `` a very effective, capable leader -LRB- who -RRB- has an opportunity to do something.'' Talking about <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s twin programs of `` glasnost,'' or openness, and `` perestroika,'' or economic reform, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, `` I think glasnost is for real. I happen to think that the Soviet society today is more open than it has been in the past, that you read publications today that you would not have read five years ago, three years ago, 10 years ago. ... `` Perestroika on the other hand I'm personally a bit more skeptical of. I think perestroika _ anytime someone tries to reform the system, particularly that system, is just a consolidation of power. I think <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s been very effective in the consolidation of power.''
