<HEAD>Dispute Over `Propaganda' Label</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration lawyer on Tuesday defended the government's attempt to label some political documentary films `` propaganda'' when approving their tax-free export, saying the label is informative, not disparaging. But a lawyer for independent filmmakers told a federal appeals court that the labeling was `` an informal system of censorship.'' The argument before the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> involved the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s latest attempt to review thousands of documentaries each year for their content before approving them as `` educational, scientific or cultural,'' which allows their tax-free export under a treaty signed by 72 nations. The agency's first regulations, which rejected films that advocated viewpoints or were deemed to misrepresent a government's policy, were declared unconstitutional by the 9th Circuit last year The current regulations would require a film to be primarily factual in its approach, to be based on a `` reasonably current state'' of available information, and to acknowledge the existence of opposing viewpoints. They would also allow the <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> to tell other countries that a film, though approved as educational, was `` propaganda'' in that it was designed to promote a political, religious or economic viewpoint. The foreign government could then decide whether to approve tax-free imports. The regulations were challenged by the makers of six documentary films. Four, on subjects that include the dangers of uranium mining, disarmanent and Agent Orange, were denied <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> approval; one, on drug use among urban youth, had been rejected under the earlier standards but was approved under the new standards; the sixth, a sympathetic portrayal of the 1979 Nicaraguan revolution, was approved but given a `` propaganda'' label. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Tashima </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> rejected the new standards last May and ordered the <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> to draft a third, content-neutral set of standards while giving provisional approval to the films. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Keats </PERSON> asked a three-judge panel Tuesday to reverse <PERSON> Tashima </PERSON>'s ruling. The 1954 treaty, known as the <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> Agreement, requires governments to evaluate films based on their contents, Ms. <PERSON> Keats </PERSON> said. She said the Constitution does not prohibit a viewpoint-neutral assessment of whether a film is presented in a factual manner, or a non-coercive statement that it is propaganda. `` On its face, the propaganda label does not either disparage a film or prevent it from being circulated,'' Ms. <PERSON> Keats </PERSON> said. She said the label merely encourages foreign governments to take a second look at a film. Claims of censorship are `` unduly patronizing -LRB- to -RRB- foreign governments,'' she said. But the filmmakers' lawyer, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, said the label was not simply neutral information, but an attempt to get foreign governments to deny tax-free import of films that should qualify under the treaty. He said <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> has already declared that it would not accept <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> films with `` propaganda'' labels. `` The <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> has said ... they do n't want these films to have benefits,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> told the court. He called the labeling `` an informal system of censorship.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government `` propaganda'' labels on some imported films were allowed in 1986 by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which observed that the labels did not prevent anyone from seeing the films. But <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said the current case is different because the labels are intended to stop foreign circulation of the films.
