<SECOND>AM-Admission Quotas,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Department Investigating Whether Harvard, UCLA Use Asian
Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal investigators are exploring whether <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> use illegal quotas to restrict the number of Asian-American students they admit, an official said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> has been collecting and analyzing statistical information on admissions at the two schools since last fall, said department spokesman <PERSON> Mahlon </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. He declined to say what sparked the probe. No conclusions have been reached, he said. Both <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> deny using quotas for any ethnic groups, and both schools point to a significant rise in enrollment of Asian-American students. At <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION>, Asian-Americans make up 22.9 percent of the freshman class, up from 17.8 percent in 1980. At <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, the number of Asian-American freshmen roughly tripled over the past decade, from 4.8 percent in 1978 to 14.2 percent this year. By comparison, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population is only about 2 percent Asian. However, <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials say Asian-Americans tend to be high academic achievers and have been applying to top colleges and universities in rising numbers. `` The real issue is not whether the number of <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> students is going up, but what percentage of qualified applicants is being accepted,'' said <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dow </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Asian-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workshop </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit educational group in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, for example, acknowledged last year that over the past decade it had admitted an average of 17 percent of all white applicants, but 13.3 percent of Asians applicants. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will review the data and send investigators to question officials on both campuses, probably before the end of the current school year. `` Statistics alone do n't always tell the story,'' he said. `` ... When you talk to admissions officers, you understand there may be non-discriminatory policies that are driving the data and creating certain patterns.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzsimmons </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s director of admissions, said Asians tend to be slightly stronger than whites on academic criteria and slightly weaker on extracurricular activities, which can count against them because <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> seeks students with diverse talents, such as music, art and leadership. In addition, he said, relatively few Asians in the applicant pool are children of alumni or prospective varsity athletes. `` When all those factors are taken into account, the difference in admission rates for the two groups disappears,'' he said. <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Lum </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> senior and co-president of the <ORGANIZATION> Asian-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> on campus, said <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> has had Asian students working in the admissions office to recruit Asian-Americans, especially from low-income families, for four years. `` It would be counterproductive to do that and impose quotas at the same time,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> stopped qualifying Asian-Americans for affirmative action when it became clear that they were overrepresented, not underrepresented, in proportion to population, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifka </PERSON>, an assistant vice chancellor responsible for admissions. <PERSON> Lifka </PERSON> said 35 percent of <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> applicants were admitted in 1988, compared with 32 percent of whites. `` We are convinced that if the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> looks at the data carefully ... they will conclude that there is no discrimination.'' If the department determines a college or university discriminates on the basis of race or ethnicity, it can block federal grants and guaranteed student loans which amount to hundreds of millions of dollars for major schools. But <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said the schools are first given an opportunity to change their disputed practices, and most do so.
