<HEAD>US Reviewing West German Chemical Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sale of a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> high-technology company to a West German chemical firm is being reviewed by a government task force in the first test of a new law that allows the president to block foreign purchases of American companies on national security grounds. The case involves the proposed sale of <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> Electronic Materials of <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, to <ORGANIZATION> Huels </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The American company, an operating division of the giant <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> chemical company headquartered in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, produces silicon wafers, the flat discs used to make computer chips. Silicon wafers are the building blocks for the semiconductor industry, a sector of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy considered vital not only for national security reasons but also for trade reasons. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s edge in the battle with foreign competitors has centered in such high-technology fields as computer manufacturing. The proposed sale to the West German company was reviewed in a closed-door meeting on Tuesday by the Committee on Foreign Investment. The committee is composed of officials from eight government agencies and is headed by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulford </PERSON>, an assistant <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary. The panel has until next Monday to forward a recommendation to the president. It is expected the proposed sale will be one of the first trade issues that President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will have to face. Originally, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> raised questions about the proposed sale. However, an attorney representing <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday he believes the original objections had been dealt with. `` We have met with -LRB- government officials -RRB- on numerous occasions. We answered all of the questions and repeat questions,'' said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Earle </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harbison </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the president of <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Krauch </PERSON>, the chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Huels </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of the giant West German conglomerate <ORGANIZATION> Veba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>, both met with officials from various agencies on Tuesday. `` There is no credible evidence that <ORGANIZATION> Huels </ORGANIZATION>, an exemplary company from a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> ally, would so something that would injure the national security of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dennin </PERSON> said. Officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said no announcement of the panel's recommendation would be released before it was reviewed by the president, who has 15 days under the law to reach a decision on the panel's findings. The review of foreign takeovers of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies on national security grounds was included in the giant Omnibus Trade Act of 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had become concerned that the wave of foreign purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies could be endangering national security. Three other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers of silicon wafers have been sold to Japanese firms in the past four years and the sale of another <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> silicon wafer supplier, the wafer division of <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milacron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Titanium </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is pending.
