<HEAD>Solidarity Ready to Resume Legal Activity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a small apartment about a mile from <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, two excited Solidarity activists tuned into the latest TV reports of a party meeting they believed would result in a decision to legalize the banned labor federation. Rarely have the long speeches at a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> plenum commanded such close attention from Solidarity, which for seven years has tried the party's patience by refusing to abandon the fight for legal existence. `` Are they registering Solidarity yet?'' yelled <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Litynski </PERSON>, spokesman for the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> region of Solidarity, to former underground Solidarity leader <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Bujak </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bujak </PERSON> had just flipped on the television switch in another room on the first day of the party debate on the future of Solidarity. He did not reply. The answer was not immediately forthcoming as party members heatedly debated for hours on Monday and Tuesday over a move to legalize Solidarity. The party had reason to be nervous. In 1980-81, during Solidarity's legal existence, an estimated 1 million party members joined the independent union movement. Thousands more turned in their party cards in disgust when <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s leader, Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, imposed martial law on Dec. 13, 1981. But on Tuesday Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> urged the party to legalize the banned union on condition that it be `` a partner,'' not an opponent that would `` pull the country into anarchy.'' <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> had vigorously defended the martial law decision in the early 1980s. The reversal in policy arises from the party's failure to eradicate Solidarity after the martial law crackdown and reflects the authorities' need to gain support from society to push through a program of radical economic reform. `` They -LRB- party leaders -RRB- are doing this because they realize they have to and it was obvious they had to,'' said <PERSON> Litynski </PERSON>, a veteran opposition activist who advised striking miners during <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s worst labor unrest in seven years last August Although the shift in the party's attitude is welcome, some Solidarity activists believe the union must proceed with caution because the change results from necessity rather than good will. `` The authorities will do whatever that have to do to stay on top. Let's wait and see what they have to say and read the fine print carefully,'' said <PERSON> Maciej </PERSON> <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON>, a Solidarity leader at <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Solidarity activists do not foresee a return to the heady days of 1980-81, when union work was a round-the-clock passion for many. But they acknowledge that a return of legal existence would change their lives. `` It would be a real tragedy for my family. I do n't have any children now and I wo n't have time for that with all my union activities,'' said <PERSON> Bujak </PERSON>, who first drew national attention when he became leader of Solidarity's <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> region in 1980 at the age of 26. <PERSON> Litynski </PERSON>, who has long dreamed of visiting the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, believes he may have to postpone any visit if Solidarity is legalized. For <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON>, regulation of the labor federation's status means he would be able to focus on solving other problems. <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON> spent Tuesday afternoon taking part in a rally at <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in support of legalizing the Independent Students' Union and Solidarity While Solidarity is eager to resume its activities legally, that status poses challenges to union leaders such as how to organize the labor federation and how to achieve economic reform. But a return to legal existence would mean that many could finally emerge from the shadows of underground publishing and from church basement meetings into a more normal way of participating in public life.
