<SECOND>AM-UN-Soviet-US,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Agree To Ease Currency Restrictions With East Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS GINSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has agreed to foreign currency exchange with some <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc allies and may lower its domestic exchange rates as a prelude to full convertibility in world markets, an official said Tuesday. The deputy chairman of <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> of the U.S.S.R, V.A. <PERSON> Pekshev </PERSON>, told a U.N.-sponsored conference on U.S.-Soviet trade that <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> officials acknowledge the need for full convertibility of the ruble but must proceed slowly. `` By Jan. 1, 1990, we would make a 100 percent increase in the ratio'' of the official domestic exchange rate, <PERSON> Pekshev </PERSON> said, in effect doubling the amount of rubles exchanged for other currencies. `` Is this a currency devaluation?'' he said. `` We wo n't get into theoretical arguments on this question.'' The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has several sets of exchange rates for domestic and foreign products, and it was not known how the proposed increase would affect the rates. Black market exchange rates are often six to seven times higher than the official rates. More than 100 Americans and Soviets, including <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet envoys to the world body, began the two-day meeting Tuesday, the first such conference held under <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> auspices. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet speakers focused mainly on Soviet economic reforms and repeatedly expressed optimism about improving relations. Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of `` perestroika,'' or restructuring, has led to an explosion of cooperative business ventures and the relaxation of some restrictions on foreign trade. But ventures have been stifled by the inconvertibility of the ruble in foreign exchange markets and by the need to operate through the Soviet state bank, which takes as much as 60 percent of hard currency earnings from each transaction. Western media have reported the possibility of changes in the official rate, which currently brings about $ 1.60 per ruble. One Soviet official has said convertibility could result in a 10-fold devaluation in the ruble. <PERSON> Pekshev </PERSON> dismissed the 10-fold figure as speculative and said officials were considering ways to move to full convertibility `` stage by stage.'' `` We're not in a position today to assert a new value of the ruble to the dollar,'' he said. He said Soviets `` have agreed to partial convertibility'' with several East European countries and were planning hard currency `` auctions'' for Soviet and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc enterprises to buy the foreign currency needed for trade with the West. Foreign businesses initially will not be allowed to participate, he said. The conference is scheduled to end Wednesday afternoon, two days before President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s inauguration. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides have said they are planning a wide-ranging review of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy toward the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> before deciding on a new agenda for relations under <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> jumped from $ 214 million in 1982 to $ 446 million the next year and were projected to dip slightly to $ 445 million in 1987, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> figures. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> decreased from $ 3.4 billion in 1984 to a projected $ 1.3 billion in 1987. Another statement said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had agreed to extend visas for Soviets wishing to continue meeting with American corporations after the conference ends. Among the U.S.-based participants in the meeting were <PERSON> Duco </PERSON> <PERSON> Akkerman </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> <PERSON> Braxmaier </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>; F.E. <PERSON> Cassidy </PERSON>, director of international development for the <LOCATION> U. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> S. </LOCATION> oil company <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Galbraith </PERSON>. Soviet officials also included the deputy minister of external economic relations and head of the Soviet delegation, Y.N. <PERSON> Chumakov </PERSON>; Deputy Oil Minister L.I. <PERSON> Filimonov </PERSON>; <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponomarev </PERSON>, the Soviet trade representative; and Soviet U.N. Ambassador <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Belonogov </PERSON>.
