<HEAD>Meese Violated Ethical Standards, Justice Department Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Adds 2 grafs of reax from Wallach attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> concluded Tuesday that former Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> violated federal ethics standards five times in six years and that his relationship with <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> `` dictated government action'' in major cases. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s assistance to scandal-plagued <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and his efforts on behalf of a proposed <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> oil pipeline involved `` three instances in which friendship'' between him and <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> caused federal actions, said the report by the department's Office of Professional Responsibility. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, who collected $ 1.3 million from <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> from 1982 to 1986, is awaiting trial in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on racketeering and other charges. He is accused of peddling his <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> connection. `` As a direct result of the preferential, improper efforts of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and his staff, the Army'' awarded a $ 32 million engine-building contract to <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 while <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was counselor to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, said the ethics report on <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> also violated ethics requirements, the report said, by failing to report a stock sale on his 1985 federal tax return and by participating in a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> decision favoring the regional <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> telephone companies in which he held $ 14,000 in stock at the time. If <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> were still attorney general, `` we would recommend -LRB- to the next ranking department official -RRB- that the president take disciplinary action,'' the report concluded. A department statement said no further action against <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> is warranted because he is no longer a government employee. Independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> decided last summer not to prosecute <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, although <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> concluded <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> had probably twice violated conflict-of-interest laws in connection with his Bell holdings and had violated tax laws in connection with failing to report the stock sales. <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s report `` far from vindicates Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>,'' said the new <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report. `` It details conduct which should not be tolerated of any government employee, especially not the attorney general of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> disagreed with one aspect of the report, saying that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s failure to dispose of his financial interest in the regional <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies resulted from a failure to get adequate legal advice rather than from intent to violate ethics standards. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> believes `` this report was unnecessary, partly because Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> has not been in the office for some time and partly because it was unwarranted.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> believes his longtime friend did nothing wrong. The former attorney general, who resigned last year, immediately attacked the report through his attorneys, who called it `` a travesty of justice.'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Korten </PERSON> said there is an `` emotional undertone'' to the report that seems designed `` to slam him personally.'' At a news conference, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> declined to defend his department's Office of Professional Responsibility from criticism by <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s supporters that the report was a personal attack on <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>. `` I think Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> is entitled to some peace,'' said <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> tried to avoid characterizing the <ORGANIZATION> OPR </ORGANIZATION> report in any way, but ultimately called one of its conclusions `` clearly wrong'' and said there is an adequate factual basis for the others. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> disagreed with the conclusion <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> violated ethical standards when he failed to sell $ 14,000 in stock of regional <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies while participating in department decisions affecting them. He said there is an `` adequate factual basis'' for finding in four instances that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> violated ethics standards. But <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said that in regard to the <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> stock, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> either did n't get adequate legal advice or did n't follow it. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> characterized that as a mistake, saying `` I've done that myself sometimes. People make mistakes. We're all human.'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> emphasized that the findings in the report were those of <ORGANIZATION> OPR </ORGANIZATION>, not of the attorney general. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, according to the report, violated ethical standards which require government employees to avoid the appearance of impropriety when carrying out official duties. But <PERSON> Korten </PERSON> said such a requirement is `` a lousy standard.'' He said appearance is a `` subjective matter. It is not an objective measure. What appears improper to one person may look OK to another.'' `` He had a close personal relationship with Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Korten </PERSON>. `` I do n't see why you can begrudge somebody of those friendships.'' The report notes at least 600 contacts between <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> beginning in 1981. It says that <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> personal injury lawyer, showered <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> with letters and memos on topics ranging from a `` diet program'' for the stocky presidential counselor to business arrangements, while meeting with <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> in some cases twice a day. Many of the memos, coming in `` a virtual torrent'' while <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was counselor to the president, contain `` a strong undercurrent'' in which <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> was `` seeking action'' from <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and his staff `` in matters in which he had a financial interest,'' said the report. It said the letters and memos from <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> either confirm a close personal relationship or `` reveal a level of presumptuousness on the part of Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> which exceeded that which one would think humanly possible.'' <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> suggested in one letter moving <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Ambassador <PERSON> Jeane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkpatrick </PERSON> to a new job, with <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> becoming her replacement. He also sent <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> a proprosed draft for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1983 State of the Union address and suggested in another memo a way to increase <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s power. He recommended moving then-White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> to the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> and assigning then-CIA Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Case