<HEAD>Thousands March To Protest Economic Policies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of workers and students marched through the streets of the capital and other cities Tuesday demanding wage increases and protesting government economic policies. The march in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paz </LOCATION> was preceded by a rally and was called by the <ORGANIZATION> Bolivian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION>, which says road blocks and strikes will follow. Similar marches took place in other cities in the interior, radio stations reported. Planning Minister <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON> said the government has included a 15 percent wage increase in its new budget and can not offer more. `` One can not wring water from rocks,'' he said in response to Workers Central wage demands. Speakers at Tuesday's rally called the government wage program `` inhuman'' and said it spells starvation for many. <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>'s minimum monthly wage is $ 40, but many food prices are comparable to those in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The conservative government of President <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Estenssoro </PERSON> says keeping a lid on wages is essential to the success of its economic program. The government has lowered inflation from 24,000 percent four years ago to 21 percent by firing 23,000 miners, closing unproductive mines, imposing strict wage controls and lifting all price controls. Social unrest has been kept in check through an emergency wage program financed by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and foreign governments. Tens of thousands of workers have been employed building roads, schools, irrigation systems and rural clinics.
