residency and the presidency of the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>. His positions pay more than $ 500,000 a year. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, 52, holds three union positions that pay about $ 160,000 annually. <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> was indicted May 16, 1986, along with <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, but died before going to trial. The indictment listed the union offices of <PERSON> Presser </PERSON>, <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> as being subject to forfeiture after a conviction. <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> declined to comment Tuesday after the verdict. Before leaving the federal court building Tuesday, he shook hands with <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> prosecutor <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Jigger </PERSON> and said: `` I know you had a job to do, and I can appreciate that.'' <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> commented publicly for the first time Tuesday on the verdict. `` They explained everything to me and I still do n't understand it. We will continue to fight,'' he said. `` I do n't think we are guilty, and I do n't understand how they would come up with a verdict like that.'' <PERSON> Jigger </PERSON> told reporters he will try to have <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> removed from their union positions. `` It was a six-year effort and we are pleased with the outcome,'' said Jigger, also commenting publicly for the first time. `` Judge <PERSON> White </PERSON> gave everyone a full and fair trial, and justice was done. It shows the system worked.'' <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> was convicted of embezzlement, labor racketeering, conspiracy to commit labor racketeering and filing a false report to the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>. He could be sentenced to as many as 46 years in prison and fined up to $ 70,000. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> was convicted of embezzlement, labor racketeering and conspiracy to commit labor racketeering. He faces up to 45 years imprisonment and a fine of up to $ 60,000. White has not set a sentencing date. The jury found <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> guilty of participating in a payroll padding scheme. The indictment alleged the $ 700,000 embezzlement took place between 1972 and 1981.
