<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     01-17 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Genesis: Music and Miracles,' A New Musical, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Genesis: Music and Miracles,'' a retelling of five medieval mystery plays, is not very musical and more mundane than miraculous. This Old Testament song and dance, which opened Tuesday off-Broadway at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION>, sounds like it was spawned in the late 1960s. The production has the earnestness but not the conviction of street theater, the relentless beat but not the soaring melodies of such pop musicals as `` Godspell'' and `` Jesus Christ Superstar'' and the simplicity but not the charm of story theater. Five episodes are told in a quick 95 minutes _ the creation and the fall of <PERSON> Lucifer </PERSON>, the creation and fall of <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> and Eve, the murder of <PERSON> Abel </PERSON>, <PERSON> Noah </PERSON> and the Flood and the story of <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> and <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON>. The results are painless and occasionally pleasant but nothing more. The stories, adapted by A.J. <PERSON> Antoon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, unfold in rhymes, many of them awkward and forced. The tales are so well known that they need a little passion, humor and inventiveness to make them fly. They do n't get that here. The best moments come in the story of <PERSON> Noah </PERSON>, and these are supplied by set designer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conklin </PERSON> who has given the actors boards and planks with which to construct a pretty spiffy ark. The designer also supplies some toy animals, wooden figures that are carried onto the boat by the actors. For a musical, the sparse score, which has music by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> and lyrics by <PERSON> Antoon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, is surprisingly wispy, sort of like the lesser love themes from the Biblical movies of Cecil B. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Mille </PERSON>. Still, the large cast remains undefeated by the material. Particularly fine is <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogardus </PERSON> who plays the pivotal roles of <PERSON> Adam </PERSON>, <PERSON> Noah </PERSON> and <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bogardus </PERSON> has a booming musical comedy voice and is a fine actor. If Broadway had more than two or three musicals a year, he always would find work. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Munger </PERSON>'s Eve is sympathetic and forthright, but she's also saddled with some of the worst lines as <PERSON> Noah </PERSON>'s shrewish wife. In one novel bit of interpretation, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> plays <PERSON> Cain </PERSON> almost like a psychotic street tough. His murder of the passive, almost nondescript <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> is brutal, unnerving and hard to watch. The red-haired <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> <PERSON> Thacker </PERSON> makes a persuasive Lucifer, a grinning, boyish sprite with a ghoulish smile. Special mention also should be made of young <PERSON> Braden </PERSON> <PERSON> Danner </PERSON> who sings in a clear, crisp style and turns <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON>'s son <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> into a credible character and not just the plot device he usually is. The choreography by <PERSON> Lynne </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor-Corbett </PERSON> does n't get past minimal and is given mostly to two dancing doubles for <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> and Eve. <PERSON> Conklin </PERSON> also designed the costumes, and they include what may be a first for the supposedly naked First Couple _ anatomically correct, flesh-colored body stockings. A very strange cover-up. Except for those inventive glad rags, ` Genesis: Music and Miracles'' offers very little that is surprising or memorable once the house lights have gone back up.
</TEXT>
