<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high school can not allow students to hold regular religious meetings in a classroom shortly before the school day starts, a federal appeals court ruled Tuesday. The ruling by the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in a case from <LOCATION> Renton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, has implications for the Equal Access Act, a 1984 federal law that requires public secondary schools to allow religious clubs to meet at school on the same basis as other extracurricular clubs. The court stopped short of declaring the law unconstitutional, saying instead that the <LOCATION> Renton </LOCATION> school system was n't affected by the law because it barred all non-curricular clubs from meeting on campus. But the court also indicated that any on-campus religious meetings would probably violate the constitutional requirement of separation of church and state. `` The district must exclude organized religious speech because use of public school facilities for religious purposes violates the Establishment Clause'' of the Constitution, which forbids a state establishment of religion, said Judge <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Farris </PERSON> in the 3-0 decision. If the ruling stands, the Equal Access Act `` has been functionally rendered impotent and would n't apply in virtually any public high school setting,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> McFarland </PERSON>, lawyer for a group of high school students in the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> suburb. He said he would appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Slonim </PERSON>, a lawyer for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION>, said the ruling may be the first by any federal appeals court on the issue but is consistent with a number of lower-court decisions around the nation. `` Since early in the 19th century we've had a tradition of trying to separate religion from public schools so public schools can serve people of a wide variety of religious beliefs,'' <PERSON> Slonim </PERSON> said. He described the `` equal access'' approach as an attempt to avoid the constitutional ban on preferential treatment of religion, but said it inevitably `` sends a message of religious partisanship in the schools.'' <PERSON> McFarland </PERSON> said about 25 students applied in the fall of 1984 to use a classroom at <ORGANIZATION> Lindbergh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> for before-school meetings of a non-denominational Christian student group for religious and moral discussions, Bible readings and prayer. The principal and school district denied the request, citing constitutional standards as well as a district policy that allowed classroom meetings only if the purposes were `` an extension of a specific program or course offering.'' The students also were rejected by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>, whose ruling was upheld Tuesday. `` Permitting this student religious group to meet in a public high school just before the start of classes would impermissibly advance rather than neutrally accommodate religion,'' <PERSON> Farris </PERSON> said in the appeals court decision. He said the meetings would take place `` at a time closely associated with a highly structured school day,'' creating an appearance of school sponsorship. Although the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 allowed a student religious group equal access to a university's facilities, the same standards do not apply to public high schools, <PERSON> Farris </PERSON> said. High school students are required to attend school and `` are less mature and more impressionable than university students,'' <PERSON> Farris </PERSON> said. `` Teachers at high schools, unlike college professors, are both educators and authority figures.'' He also said the meetings would improperly `` entangle'' the government with religion, because teachers, required by district policy to supervise all student activities on campus, might either interfere with or advocate religious activities as the club's supervisor
</TEXT>
