<HEAD>Solo Inaugural Prayer Is By Longtime Bush Buddy, Graham</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Prayer for presidential integrity and courage by evangelist <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> this Friday brackets <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s inauguration. The ceremony starts with an invocation of divine assistance and ends with a benediction. `` I'm going to ask God to give the new president strength, courage and wisdom,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> says. `` I'm going to pray that he be given the wisdom to know what's right, and the courage to do it.'' Although inaugural ceremonies ordinarily include prayers by a denominational cross-section of clergy, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> this time chose for it only the durable evangelist, a long-time friend and vacation companion. `` I do n't know why I'm the only one,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said when asked about it. `` I guess he and <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> must have felt I could represent the others. I'm honored to have been selected.'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, who has been a confidant of presidents ever since <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> in the 1950's, is particularly close to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his family, and has been for about a quarter century. They regularly spend some time together each year at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s vacation home in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON>, also spent a holiday with the Bushes in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> became vice president `` I knew his father and used to play golf with him,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> related of the late Sen. <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, whose hospitality drew the <ORGANIZATION> Grahams </ORGANIZATION> into the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> orbit in the early 1960's. `` We've been close friends of the Bushes for many years,'' related <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, now 70, who in his half-century, globe-girdling career has preached directly to more than 100 million people in more than 65 countries. The new president, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said, `` has a huge family. There are a lot of Bushes and Walkers -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s mother's maiden name -RRB-. They're all very religious people. I know all the children very well. They're all religious. After dinner at the <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION> weekends, he related, `` we all gather in the living room and sit around on the floor. I read some Scipture and the children ask questions about the Bible.'' Asked why <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is n't as openly expressive of his faith as outgoing President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said, chuckling, `` Well, you see, he's an Episcopalian.'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> himself is a Baptist. Of the long line of presidents which <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> has been associated, he said, `` I think <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> went to church more than any of them,'' although <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> also was a regular church-goer and taught an adult class. `` <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has talked a lot about God,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> observed. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> has scrupulously avoided taking sides in presidential campaigns, whatever his personal associations, particularly after a non-committal ceremonial appearance with <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> caused accusation of partisanship. At last summers national political conventions, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> led prayers both at the Democratic and Republican affairs. However, while he has been a frequent White House guest and counselor through a string of eight presidents, he has a special niche in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> retinue because of their background. `` I think he'll make a far greater president than some people give him credit for,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> probably has more knowledge of what is going on in the world and more government experience than any man that has ever occupied the White House.'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, who in recent years has condemned the nuclear arms buildup, said the developing friendlier relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> `` is one of the great legacies'' being passed on by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> added, `` I definitely think <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will advance this new warmth between our two countries.'' In the inaugural prayer, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said he would quote <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> as saying that `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> stands on two great pillars _ faith and morality. Without these, our foundation crumbles. `` Sometimes, this seems to be happening, but there also are signs that a new spiritual tide is running in this nation. I'm going to thank God for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and all it stands for. `` I'm also going to say that humantity's promotion comes neither from the East or the West, but from God.'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said his inaugural prayer also would ask blessings on <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> as Vice President, on his wife, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>, and for the coninued `` health and service'' of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>.
