<FIRST>r f PM-RetailPredictions Bjt   01-17 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Predictions, Bjt,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Few Surprises in Retail Forecasts: More Slow Sales In 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retailers from across the country, gathered for their annual convention, have heard an unsurprising forecast from industry watchers: Sales will remain sluggish in 1989. <PERSON> Rosalind </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> told storeowners Monday that consumers are optimistic and confident about the economy, but retail sales will increase only 6 percent _ 2.75 percent after inflation. Americans have already put a lot of big purchases behind them, and `` there's much less pent-up demand,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramley </PERSON>, chief economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, were upbeat about the economy although they did not expect consumer spending to surge. <PERSON> Gramley </PERSON> said he saw no signs of a recession this year. He did see some negatives ahead, including a slight worsening of inflation that would help to nudge interest rates higher. But he said he expected interest rates to peak by mid-year. If significant steps are taken to cut the federal budget, rates could decline before year's end, he said. The forecasters spoke at the <ORGANIZATION> NRMA </ORGANIZATION>'s four-day convention here. The delegates included retailers ranging from owners of small shops to executives of the nation's largest storeowner, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Roebuck </PERSON> and Co. The economic forecasting session traditionally is one of the biggest of the meeting, drawing thousands of retailers away from the aisles of exhibits set up by cash register manufacturers and credit card companies. Another industry watcher, <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON>, an analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said he expected `` more of the same kind of muddling along'' in the economy this year, resulting in a mediocre retail environment. <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON> said, `` I do n't feel good about 5 and 6 percent'' sales increases, recalling that in past years, retailers enjoyed 9 percent or 10 percent gains. Forecasts of consumer spending are critical for retailers, because they must adjust their inventories and expenses in line with how much Americans spend. Economists also watch consumer spending because it accounts for two-thirds of the gross national product, the broadest measure of economic health. In recent years, consumer spending has increased although retail sales have risen only slightly. Americans have been channeling more dollars into buying homes and cars and into necessities such as food and medical care, leaving less money for discretionary items, which include clothing and furniture. High installment debt has been blamed for some of the retail sales slump, which is nearly 2 years old. But despite the forecasts of higher interest rates, Ms. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> was unconcerned about consumer debt. Although they may owe more money, buying on credit is such a way of life that `` people are more comfortable with debt,'' she said. <PERSON> Gramley </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> both expected job growth to slow. That would affect retailers because new workers have been a primary source of sales increases in recent years. Durable goods, such as cars, furniture and large appliances, would bear the brunt of consumer hesitance, while non-durables, such as food, clothing and gasoline, should see pickups, Ms. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON> had a warning for the retailers: No matter what sales do, operating expenses will climb. Storeowners have been paring costs in the past few years to preserve their profits as sales declined. But <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON> said expenses would spurt higher because as costs of labor, goods and real estate accelerate. The forecasters also said there were many other variables that may affect business during the year, such as the volatile price of oil.
</TEXT>
