<HEAD>National Semiconductor Announces Plan to Lay Off 2,000, Reorganize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to lay off about 2,000 workers worldwide was based on slow demand and dipping prices but will allow the company to recover its financial health by summer, company officials and analysts said The layoffs are part of a company reorganization announced Monday in a move allowing <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> to focus on its primary business _ advanced semiconductors. The company, which designs, manufactures and markets advanced semiconductor products, currently employs about 39,000 people worldwide. `` While we expect slow growth this calendar year, in line with industry levels, our management remains optimistic about the long-term outlook for our company,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION>. `` We believe this action will allow us to focus on our core business and to maintain the company's growth and long-term health,'' said <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON>. National Semiconductor's action follows the layoff of nearly 2,500 employees by <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Micro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Devices </ORGANIZATION>, 1,000 of them in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> AMD </ORGANIZATION> blamed a soft market, while analysts said poor management also contributed significantly to the company's financial problems. A weakening demand for semiconductors and, by extension, personal computers in the second half of 1988 affected most major Silicon Valley manufacturers. But shrewd management practices helped most companies _ from <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> _ avoid layoffs. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> semiconductor industry's monthly ratio of orders to shipments slipped to its lowest point of the year in December, according to figures released last Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The figure meant that for every $ 100 in products shipped, there were $ 93 in new orders. The figure for new orders reached a high of $ 1.18 in April, and has fallen every month except one since then. <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION>, a high-technology consulting firm, has predicted the semiconductor industry will experience modest growth of about 10 percent for the rest of this year, down from 36 percent last year. National Semiconductor's layoffs will occur at all levels in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, with about 50 percent of the cuts being made domestically, said company spokeswoman <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Coady </PERSON>. The company also will take a one-time restructuring charge in the third quarter of its current fiscal year. Company officials could n't immediately say what that charge will be, although the information should be available within a few days, <PERSON> Coady </PERSON> said. For the first half of fiscal 1989, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> reported a net loss of $ 55.7 million. In the latest quarter, the company posted a net loss of $ 25 million on revenue of $ 705 million. Company officials said the layoffs will allow <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> to achieve two goals: a corporate reorganization and bringing costs and staffing into line with declining revenues in the semiconductor industry. `` Companies are n't buying as many personal computers,'' said <PERSON> Coady </PERSON>. `` Luckily we are a broad-based supplier.'' The drop in revenues also was caused by an inventory adjustment by distributors who bought very heavily in the summer and had built up huge supplies, analysts said. <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelps </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Hambrecht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Quist in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, predicted the company is `` getting healthy again'' and will break even this quarter and begin to turn a profit by the end of fiscal year 1990, if it can work through the `` price dropping issue.'' `` They now have a fix on where they are going with sales and know what the level of business will be and what work force will be needed for that,'' <PERSON> Phelps </PERSON> said. The layoffs will likely be permanent unless there is a surprise large upswing in the market, <PERSON> Phelps </PERSON> said.
