<HEAD>Steel Industry Capacity to Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's ability to produce steel will increase this year after declining for seven consecutive years, according to the American Iron and <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. The industry's raw steel production capability is expected to reach 115.9 million tons this year, up from 112 million tons in 1988, the low point of the decade. The figure was projected from a December survey of all mills with furnaces for melting, the institute said Monday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steelmakers had facilities capable of producing 160 million tons of steel per year in 1977, the highest on record. The projected increase from 1988 to 1989 is mostly a result of newer and more efficient equipment. Those capital investments have paid off with increased yield of finished products per ton of raw steel, the institute said. The average yield is now close to 85 percent, compared with 71.5 percent 10 years ago.
</TEXT>
