<HEAD>Dollar Rises Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar gained sharply against the Japanese yen today, reflecting its sharp rise on overseas markets overnight, and stock prices fell in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. The dollar opened at 127.93 yen and went as high as 128.15 yen in early trading before easing back to 127.70 yen at the finish, up 1.05 yen from the close of 126.65 yen last Friday, when the dollar gained 0.53 yen. The market was closed Monday for a national holiday. Finance Minister <PERSON> Tatsuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Murayama </PERSON> attributed the dollar's strength to the difference in key interest rates between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and to reported statements by West German finance authorities that the dollar's current level is acceptable. He ruled out the possibility of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> intervening to stem the dollar's rise, saying, `` The situation does not require immediate countermeasures.'' Traders noted that on Monday, the dollar closed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at 128.05 yen and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at 128.10. One reason for the gains, they said, was reduced chances of central bank intervention as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> observed a holiday and many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> traders were absent from the market in observance of the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s birthday. `` There had been strong demand for buying the dollar, but traders' fears over intervention prevented such a move,'' said a dealer at a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` Then when they were freed from such fears, they all went out to buy the dollar.'' But the traders added that the dollar was unlikely to continue gaining while the market awaited <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade reports due Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues dipped 70.86 points, or 0.23 percent, closing at 31,227.52. Dealers said the dollar's steep gain and anxiety over the upcoming <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade reports contributed to the decline as many investors pulled back to the sidelines. Prices of export-oriented issues fell, as did those of steel, railway and petroleum shares. `` It appeared the market was taking a break today as the market anxiously awaits the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade reports,'' said a dealer at a major Japanese brokerage. `` But the yen's sharp downslide against the dollar gave a downward direction and most shares ended up lower.'' But most dealers appeared to take today's decline as temporary. `` The market is still bullish despite today's slip,'' said <PERSON> Ichitaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` I think it still has potential for further growth.''
