<HEAD>Supreme Court Rules Against Amputee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> man who lost a leg in a farm accident lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> bid today to revive his lawsuit against a farm equipment manufacturer. The justices, without comment, rejected arguments that the lawsuit was dismissed improperly because a stenographer was tardy in transcribing pretrial statements. The accident occurred Oct. 22, 1983, when <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> was unloading corn from a wagon into an old house used for grain storage. His clothing was caught in the portable conveyor connecting a tractor to the corn elevator, and his left leg had to be severed. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, threw out the suit against <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bloomington </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, the conveyor manufacturer. <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> said the conveyor's design was defective and was inherently dangerous. <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON>'s own negligence _ his failure to stand far enough away from the machine _ caused the accident. The company also said the machine had been modified since its manufacture and that <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> ws not responsible for the changes. <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> threw out the suit on June 30, 1987 without reviewing depositions _ or pretrial statements _ from witnesses for <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON>. An engineer said in the deposition that the conveyor was defective because it lacked a guard to prevent such accidents. The engineer also said any changes in the machinery were minor and had little bearing on the accident. The 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last June that it was <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON>'s responsibility to make sure that a transcript of the statement was provided to the judge. `` Without the deposition testimony, -LRB- <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> -RRB- has presented no evidence of design defect,'' the appeals court said. <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON>'s lawyers said the stenographer, called a court reporter, violated federal court rules by failing to supply the judge with the statement. The lawyers said, unbeknownst to them, the stenographer sent a transcript of the deposition to attorneys for <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> but not to <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>. <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> was `` denied his day in court beacuse of the failure of a court reporter to follow the federal rules,'' attorneys said. They also said that federal appeals courts elsewhere in the nation have reinstated suits in such cases. The case is <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, 88-758.
</TEXT>
