<HEAD>London Stocks Close Lower On Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: updates throughout with close.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices closed lower Tuesday as players took profits on the market's strong rally in recent weeks. Trading volume also was lower amid caution ahead of a string of economic statistics due out later this week. Key among these is Wednesday's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade report for November. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index finished 4.1 points, or 0.2 percent, lower at 1,867.7. Volume fell to 424.2 million shares from Monday's 497 million shares. Since the start of the year, the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market has declined in just three of its 11 trading sessions, and dealers said it was due for some selling. Aside from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade report, players also are awaiting news on British employment and average earnings, due Thursday, and British inflation figures, scheduled for release on Friday. While Monday's news of a slowing in British retail sales in December was welcomed, the market is hoping the additional reports will confirm that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s interest rate hikes are beginning to ease inflationary pressures on the economy.
