<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-USTrade Bjt   01-17 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Trade, Bjt,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Cheaper Dollar Could Backfire on U.S. Trade Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pushing the dollar lower against the Japanese yen to help shrink the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit could have the opposite effect in the long term as Japanese businesses become more competitive, a senior <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official said Tuesday. <PERSON> Makoto </PERSON> <PERSON> Utsumi </PERSON>, director general of the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, also said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses were fully competitive at current exchange rates even though they had problems competing in foreign arenas `` A further decline in the dollar would not reduce the Japanese trade surplus,'' <PERSON> Utsumi </PERSON> told reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correspondents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` If the dollar weakens further, Japanese businesses would take steps to survive by further rationalization of business and manufacturing, keeping wage increases low, cutting labor further _ economy in every aspect,'' <PERSON> Utsumi </PERSON> said. `` After this process of rationalization, Japanese manufacturers might be still more competitive,'' and paying lower prices in dollar terms for imported raw materials would give them a further advantage, he said. Japanese manufacturers responded to the first major appreciation of the yen against the dollar in 1985-1986 by improving efficiency after the major industrialized nations, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, agreed to slash the dollar's value to help shrink the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. In February 1987, those nations agreed on approximate exchange rate ranges for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar and other major currencies, seeking to restore stability to exchange markets, but the dollar continued to slide from its September 1985 level of 240 yen. The dollar closed at 127.70 yen Tuesday in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. It has ranged between 120 yen and 135 yen since November 1987. Economists remain divided over the actual impact of a cheaper dollar on trade flows. Some say the cheaper dollar has helped narrow the trade gap by dampening demand for more expensive foreign goods in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and stimulating sales of cheaper American goods overseas. They also say the dollar would have to drop to 80 yen or lower to achieve desired reductions in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. But <PERSON> Utsumi </PERSON> said further declines in the dollar's value would not improve American export competitiveness. `` The problem is not price competitiveness of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries, but the willingness and capacity to export,'' <PERSON> Utsumi </PERSON> said. Using exchange rates to boost exports has the disadvantage of encouraging manufacturers to concentrate on fattening their profit margins rather than improving productivity, <PERSON> Utsumi </PERSON> stated. The senior ministry official urged the incoming administration of President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to cut the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> federal budget deficit and curb consumer demand. `` Then <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers would become more eager to seek out overseas markets to sell their products,'' he said. <PERSON> Utsumi </PERSON> said little remains to be done by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s government to open its markets to foreign exporters. Instead, the question is `` how to crack the ice of the private sector,'' he said. He predicted <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s current account surplus would decline by several billion dollars in fiscal 1988, which ends March 31, and by another several billion dollars in fiscal 1989. In 1987, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s surplus in the current account, which measures trade in goods and services, flows of short-term interest and dividends, repatriation of profits and other financial transfers, was $ 86.7 billion, up from $ 85.8 billion in 1986. Its surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> hit a record $ 59.8 billion in 1987, up from $ 58.6 billion in 1986. In 1986, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s current account surplus amounted to 3.6 percent of its gross national product, and was expected to amount to a little over 2 percent this year, <PERSON> Utsumi </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
