<FIRST>u f PM-AgingAircraft 1stLd-Writethru   01-17 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aging Aircraft, 1st Ld-Writethru,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Expects Dozens Of FAA Orders to Modify Older Planes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `FAA officials ... ,' with 1 graf to UPDATE
with Boeing comment on possible number of orders.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENTON, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The mid-flight disintegration of part of a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 over <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> is likely to lead to as many as 50 orders to strengthen older passenger jets in the next year, a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> executive says. In the meantime, <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON>, vice president for engineering at <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION>, said the world's largest commercial jet manufacturer is making sure the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is told of problems in older planes. At a news briefing on aging aircraft, <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> said that when <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> officials hear about an aircraft problem from an airline, they tell the carrier to notify the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> within 24 hours, `` and we make sure that it does.'' The <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> accident last April stunned the commercial aircraft industry and raised questions about older aircraft and how long they can safely fly. The <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 was flying over <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> when an 18-foot section ripped from the top of the jetliner. A flight attendant was swept to her death and 64 of the 93 other people aboard were hurt before the crew managed to land the plane on <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION>. The 19-year-old plane, with nearly 90,000 flights, was the second most-heavily used plane in the worldwide 737 fleet. Last June, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> sponsored a three-day conference in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, on older planes. One result was the creation of task forces of <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, manufacturer and airline representatives to examine ways to ensure older planes' safety. Since the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has changed some of its thinking about older aircraft, sometimes requiring operators to make specific modifications rather than just checking for a given problem and correcting it if trouble is found. Last fall, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> required operators of many older 737s to replace thousands of rivets in some places where a 737's skin is joined after the adhesive used on those lap joints was found prone to delamination. In December, a similar order was issued for older <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 tri-jets. <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON>, who serves on a working group that oversees task forces dealing with <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> planes, said it has reviewed service bulletins <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> has issued over the years as advisories for 727, 737 and 747 jumbo jets operators and has nearly completed recomending which ones airlines now should be required to perform. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> will then determine which modifications should be made mandatory through `` airworthiness directives,'' or orders to air carriers, he said. `` You're going to see ads coming out pretty quick on some recommendations,'' he said, adding later that as many as `` 50, 51'' directives could be issued in the next 12 months. In addition to the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> planes, other work groups are examining aircraft made by <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell-Douglas </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrie </ORGANIZATION>, Convair, <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> and British Aircraft. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said the number of directives involving older <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> airframes could be as few as 10 or 12, and that the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> may group some smaller modifications into single directives to make the process simpler. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> officials and many others in the industry say commercial planes can be flown indefinitely, as long as they are properly maintained. What determines an airplane's life, they say, is the increasing cost of maintenance, the aircraft's efficiency, and technological changes. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> report on causes of the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident is expected out shortly, and <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> said he would wait until it is released before commenting on why that massive structural failure occurred.
</TEXT>
