<HEAD>Dollar Ends Lower In Europe, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar fell in choppy European trading Tuesday as activity ebbed in advance of Wednesday's release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for November. Gold prices rose. Dealers said investors were selling dollars to take profits before the trade figures are released. Economists expected the November deficit to have widened to $ 11.1 billion from $ 10.35 billion in October. The market also believed the dollar was too high after its big jump Monday, dealers said. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency began to recover in late trading after it began to rally in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> obviously still likes the buck,'' said a chief dealer at a British bank, noting that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> players have been more bullish than their European counterparts recently. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost $ 1.7680 to buy one pound, dearer than $ 1.7615 Monday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday's prices, included: 1.8505 West German marks, down from 1.8575; 1.5755 Swiss francs, down from 1.5835; 6.3085 French francs, down from 6.3285; 2.0855 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0965; 1,354.00 Italian lire, down from 1,359.50; and 1.1973 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1965 In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 1.05 yen to a closing 127.70 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 127.75 yen. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 402.25 a troy ounce, compared with $ 401.75 bid late Monday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid $ 402.15, compared with $ 401.35 bid late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 1.78 to close at a bid $ 404.43. Silver bullion prices rose on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 5.92 a troy ounce, compared with Monday's $ 5.89.
