<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar slipped Tuesday in quiet trading, reflecting money-dealer reluctance to take risky positions in the currency prior to the release of the potentially market-moving monthly trade deficit report. Gold prices rose slightly after declining in the previous trading session. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> quoted bullion at $ 402.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $ 401.80 at the same time Monday. Currency strategists said the dollar's decline signaled a cautious approach by dollar holders toward the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Wednesday release of the November <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> merchandise trade deficit statistics The consensus is for a shortfall of about $ 11 billion, compared with $ 10.35 billion the month before, but the numbers are renowned for defying predictions. A number sharply higher than $ 11 billion could possibly incite a big selloff in dollars, while a much smaller number could encourage a surge in demand for the currency. In either case, the uncertainty of whether central banks would intervene to stabilize the dollar's value with massive purchases or sales of their own also encouraged caution in the market, currency traders said. `` It was a very quiet day, with people squaring their positions ahead of the release of the number,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Scala </PERSON>, senior foreign exchange dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Over the past few years the trade deficit numbers have become a powerful influence over the foreign-exchange market, because of their role in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic policy as well as their unpredictability from month to month. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar rose 1.05 yen to 127.70 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> it was quoted at 127.75 yen. By the time trading ended in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar was quoted at 127.83 yen, down from 128.10 yen late Monday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> the British pound strengthened to $ 1.7680 vs. $ 1.7615 Monday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the pound fetched $ 1.7707, more expensive than its $ 1.7610 exchange value late Monday. Other late-dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> compared with rates late Monday: 1.8495 West German marks, down from 1.8565; 1.5746 Swiss francs, down from 1.5845; 1.1982 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1979; 6.3065 French francs, down from 6.3245; and 1,355.375 Italian lire, down from 1,359.50. Other late-dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Monday: 1.8505 marks, down from 1.8575; 1.5755 Swiss francs, down from 1.5835; 6.3085 French francs, down from 6.3285; 2.0855 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0965; 1,354.00 Italian lire, down from 1,359.50; and 1.1973 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1965. In precious metals trading, gold for current delivery rose 50 cents a troy ounce to $ 402.70 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, gold rose 50 cents an ounce to $ 402.25; in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> it rose 80 cents to $ 402.15; and in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> it rose $ 1.78 to $ 404.43. Silver for current delivery rose 5.4 cents a troy ounce to $ 5.944 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Comex </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> silver rose 3 cents an ounce to $ 5.92.
