<HEAD>Citicorp, J.P. Morgan, Security Pacific, Wells Fargo Report Higher
Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest bank holding company, and three other big banking concerns reported sharply higher earnings Tuesday for both the fourth-quarter of 1988 and the whole year. Most of the banks, which included <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said they were helped partly by tighter cost controls and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s resumption of interest payments on foreign loans. The earnings of all four banks were severely hurt in 1987 _ the peak of the Third World debt crisis _ when <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> halted interest payments on bank loans and other economically troubled countries negotiated to restructure their debt. <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> said earnings for the three months ended Dec. 31 totaled $ 747 million, or $ 2.19 a share, compared with $ 621 million, or $ 1.82 a share, in the comparable 1987 quarter. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings totaled $ 1.85 billion, or $ 5.36 a share. That compared with a loss of $ 1.18 billion in 1987, when the company decided to increase its provision to cover possible losses from shaky Third World debt. <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's fourth largest banking company, earned $ 258.1 million in the fourth quarter, or $ 1.38 a share, compared with the $ 224.1 million, or $ 1.21 a share, earned in 1987 fourth quarter. The company's 1988 earnings totaled $ 1.00 billion, or $ 5.38 a share, compared with $ 83.3 million, or 39 cents a share, in the previous year. Security Pacific, ranked sixth, said quarterly earnings totaled $ 169.5 million, or $ 1.46 a share, vs. a loss of $ 39.4 million the previous year. Its annual earnings reached $ 638.9 million, or $ 5.59 a share, vs. $ 15.7 million, or a penny a share, in 1987. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> <PERSON> Fargo </PERSON>, ranked 10th, said fourth quarter earnings were $ 136 million, or $ 2.45 a share, up 22 percent from $ 111.2 million, or $ 1.96 a share, in 1987. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings totaled $ 512.5 million, or $ 9.20, vs. $ 50.8 million, or 52 cents, in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> said all sectors of the company did well partly due to tighter expense controls. The company said quarterly and annual earnings included, among other things, $ 436 million from nearly two years of accumulated Brazilian interest payments and $ 160 million from tax benefits stemming from its $ 3 billion addition in loan-loss reserves in May 1987. <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> said it received $ 240 million of past-due interest from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> during the final quarter of 1988. On top of that, its loan-loss provision shrank, to $ 200 million for all of 1988 from $ 960 million in 1987. Security Pacific said the recognition of Brazilian interest payments accounted for $ 58 million of the increase in net interest income. It said results also reflected slow growth in non-interest expenses. <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> said losses on loans to developing companies totaled $ 663.6 million in 1988 as a result of loan sales and other measures that reduced its debt exposure. At year's end, the company had reduced non-trade related developing country debt to $ 520 million, down from $ 950 million as of Sept. 30, 1988, and $ 1.8 billion at the end of 1987. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> <PERSON> Fargo </PERSON> said the provision for its loan losses in the fourth quarter was $ 75 million, down from $ 114 million a year ago. The full-year provision was $ 300 million, compared with $ 892 million in 1987.
