<HEAD>Corn Futures Plunge Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn futures prices plunged Tuesday for the second straight day on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid rumors of export cancellations in a market already weakened by the government's report of larger-than-expected supplies. Soybean futures also fell sharply while wheat and oat futures finished mostly higher. On other other markets, gasoline futures led energy futures higher; precious metals advanced; livestock and meat futures were mostly higher; and stock-index futures retreated. Wheat settled 2 cents to 6 cents higher with the contract for delivery in March at $ 4.36 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 10 -LCB- cents lower with March at $ 2.67 -RCB- a bushel; oats were unchanged to 2 -LCB- cents higher with March at $ 2.33 a bushel; and soybeans were 14 -LCB- cents lower to 1 cent higher with March at $ 7.70 -RCB- a bushel. Rumors that port congestion may force the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to cancel some of its purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn, soybeans or soybean meal weighed on the futures markets for those commodities, analysts said. Under a long-term grain agreement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has so far agreed to purchase more than 10 million tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn, 1.1 million tons of soybean meal, 450,000 tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybeans and 370,000 tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat for 1988-89 delivery. The cancellation rumors had the greatest impact in the corn pit, where intra-day losses approached the 15-cents-a-bushel limit. The Board of Trade expanded the daily trading limit for corn from 10 cents a bushel following limit declines on Monday. Analysts said the rumors surfaced just as the corn and soybean markets appeared to be recovering from Monday's collapse, which was linked to an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> crop report released Friday that indicated that supplies of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn and soybeans were larger than most market experts had expected. `` When people started talking about net cancellations of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales by the <LOCATION> Russians </LOCATION>, that brought in a pretty bearish attitude right up until the close,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Freed </PERSON>, a grain market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Additional selling of soybean futures was prompted by reports of improved growing conditions in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, where a spate of hot, dry weather got the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soybean crop off to a bad start, analysts said. A late rally brought corn and soybean futures off their lows of the day. But corn for near-month delivery still closed at its lowest point since Dec. 20 and January soybeans finished at $ 7.61 -RCB-, the lowest soybean futures price since Dec. 5. `` The market is searching for support now following the liquidation as a result of the crop report,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, a grain-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Freed predicted corn prices would stabilize after Tuesday's sell-off `` The market will go to wherever the demand price is,'' he said. `` My feeling is that do n't have to go down too much farther in corn'' to attract buyers. Contracts for deferred deliveries of unleaded gasoline soared the 2-cents-a-gallon daily limit on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on speculation that new pollution-control standards taking effect this year in several Northeastern states will raise the price of gasoline production, analysts said. The new regulations in states including <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> create a more stringent standard for a characteristic of gasoline that is related to automobile exhaust emissions, said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Crude oil for near-month delivery finished the day at a new 14-month high of $ 18.95 a barrel after trading as high as $ 19.21. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 30 cents higher with February at $ 18.95; heating oil was .11 cent lower to .13 cent higher with February at 53.05 cents a gallon; ands unleaded gasoline was .19 cent to 2 cents higher with February at 51.10 cents a gallon. Gold and silver futures advanced on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, reflecting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar's weakness against major foreign currencies. Gold settled 70 cents to 80 cents higher with February at $ 404 a troy ounce; silver was 5.3 cents to 5.4 cents higher with March at $ 6.01 a troy ounce. On the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, live cattle settled unchanged to .30 cent higher with February at 74.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .40 cent higher with January at 85 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower to .22 cent higher with February at 44.92 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .25 cent lower to .23 cent higher with February at 42.25 cents a pound. Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for March delivery of stocks represented by the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index settled .60 point lower at 286.10. The contract is worth $ 500 a point.
