<HEAD>Merger Business In Software, Services, Rose 70 Percent In 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar value of acquisitions in the computer software and services industry shot up 70 percent in 1988, according to a survey released Tuesday. Among the 434 deals done last year were a record 14 valued at more than $ 100 million, according to <ORGANIZATION> Broadview </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, an investment banker that does a quarterly survey for Adapso, the computer software and services industry association. Overall, the transactions were valued at a record $ 8.4 billion, up from $ 4.9 billion in 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Broadview </ORGANIZATION> said. The number of deals rose 21 percent from 358 in 1987. The biggest deal was the $ 1.6 billion purchase of <ORGANIZATION> IMS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Broadview </ORGANIZATION> said. Many of the buyers were big companies that preferred to buy established companies rather than try to build software and services businesses from scratch. For private companies, being acquired can enrich the original owners while giving their company the resources to continue its growth. The alternative of making a public stock offering is unattractive in the current market, <ORGANIZATION> Broadview </ORGANIZATION> said.
