<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-FannieMae     01-17 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Fannie Mae,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fannie Mae's Net Off in Fourth Quarter But Record High in Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday reported a 22 percent drop in fourth-quarter income from the year before, but for all of 1988 profit rose to a record level. <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION>, as the federally-chartered private corporation is commonly known, said after-tax income totaled $ 152.7 million, or $ 1.91 a share, in the final three months of 1988, down from $ 195 million, or $ 2.42 a share, in the corresponding 1987 quarter. Results for the entire year were better. In 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION> had after-tax income of $ 506.7 million, up 34.8 percent from $ 376 million the prior year and a record annual amount. That translated to per-share earnings of $ 6.43 and $ 4.66 in the two respective periods. `` <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION>'s record 1988 income successfully caps a year in which the company celebrated the 50th anniversary of its creation and its 20th year as a private company,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer. <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION> is the nation's largest investor in home mortgages. <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> attributed last year's earnings growth to an increase in the spread between the yield on the corporation's investment portfolio and the cost of its debt outstanding, an increase in the company's average investment portfolio, continued expansion in fee income from mortgage-backed securities and a decline in the tax rate. Also beneficial was a decline in properties having to be taken over due to foreclosures. Such acquisitions have fallen in each of the past five quarters. The provision for losses on mortgage loans was reduced in the fourth quarter to $ 85 million from $ 120 million in 1987's final quarter. Part of the reason for the drop in the latest quarterly earnings was that the 1987 results included adjustments associated with changes undertaken following implementation of a new accounting standard. Without the changes, earnings in the fourth 1987 quarter would have been $ 60 million, or 75 cents a share and earnings for all of that year would have been $ 242 million, or $ 2.98 a share. As of Dec. 31, <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION>'s assets totaled $ 112.1 billion, up 8.5 percent from $ 103.5 billion at the end of 1987.
