<HEAD>Court Orders Insurance Companies Into Receivership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liability </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> were ordered by the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> into receivership Tuesday at the request of state Insurance Commissioner <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>. The action was prompted by concerns over the <PERSON> Wakefield </PERSON> companies' reserve capacity to cover primarily high-risk policies written in the 1960s and 1970s involving asbestos, medical malpractice and toxic waste claims, Singer said Under the order, which was supported by the companies, Singer was named receiver and the companies were enjoined from issuing new policies or proceeding with their business except as permitted by Singer. The companies were authorized to continue paying automobile, worker's compensation and certain disability and accident and health claims, but will not renew or write new policies. The companies, formed 101 years ago, are licensed in all 50 states but primarily operate in the Northeast. They have 20,000 commercial policies nationwide and nearly 75,000 personal policies. Singer said the order was intended to protect policyholders while the Insurance Division works with management `` in an effort to improve the companies' financial condition.'' The Insurance Division will report back to the high court within 30 days on `` whether to rehabilitate them in some ways or declare them insolvent,'' Singer said. `` We will either have a plan to somehow get them back on their feet or we'll have the court declare them insolvent.'' Singer and company spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Synder </PERSON> said there is a possibility that a portion of the companies may be sold. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> has signed a letter of intent to buy a small, stock-controlled subsidiary of the companies, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policyholders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which is unaffected by the order although it too will stop writing new policies. Singer said <PERSON> National </PERSON> <PERSON> Grange </PERSON> has expressed interest in buying American Policyholders, bringing 500 to 600 of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION>'s nearly 800 <ORGANIZATION> Wakefield </ORGANIZATION> headquarters employees on board and paying off <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION>'s long-term claims `` One of the big assets of this company -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is a well-trained, experienced work force,'' Singer said. <PERSON> Synder </PERSON> said National Grange will be reviewing the potential acquisition over the next 30 days. In the meantime, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> will be looking at cutting its total 1,400-employee work force to handle only claims, <PERSON> Synder </PERSON> said. No decision on layoffs has been made yet. Singer said the companies' reserve capacity has been under review by the Insurance Division since 1985. Since then, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> has brought in new management, sold off assets and upgraded its business. `` During the past several years, the company has made great strides in strengthening its reserves to pay losses,'' American Mutual President <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wortman </PERSON> said. `` The reserve accounts have been strengthened by over $ 250 million since 1986. `` However, some very recent changes in payment patterns on old losses indicate that even more reserves may be necessary,'' he said. Singer said the discovery a few weeks ago of $ 500 million to $ 700 million in potential long-term claim exposure prompted one investor interested in buying all three companies to back out and the Insurance Division's decision to seek the receivership order. <PERSON> Synder </PERSON> said it was unclear what direction <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> will take in 30 days. But he said, `` We, obviously, are not going to be the size or shape of company that we were in the past. It all depends on what we can bring out of this.''
</TEXT>
