<HEAD>Apple Plans to Cut Some Prices; Earnings Up 16 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to CORRECT Loren's title, division president
sted president, and ADD quote; picks up 7th graf, ``Unit sales ....</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced plans to cut prices on some of its Macintosh line on Tuesday and then saw its stock drop sharply in heavy trading. The announcement coincided with the company releasing figures for its first fiscal quarter that showed it had a 16 percent increase in earnings compared to a year earlier. The stock fell $ 3.37 -LCB- a share, or 8 percent, to $ 40.62 -LCB- in the over-the-counter market. Some analysts said the stock's sudden spill was unjustified. `` It's a highly nervous market and <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> is a highly visible stock,'' said analyst <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Lupatkin </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Hambrecht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Quist. `` There's nothing wrong and <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> is stronger than ever,'' said <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bajarin </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Creative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategies </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> said it will decrease prices in its <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> division on some Macintosh personal computers, memory expansion kits and hard disk drives. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Loren </PERSON>, the division president, said the company hoped the price cuts on its more advanced models of Macintosh would bring more customers to them. `` Unit sales increased over 30 percent in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and at an even greater rate internationally,'' he said. `` But we also experienced a shift in the unit mix toward less-costly, less-configured Macintosh systems.'' He said the company `` decided to selectively drop prices in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> to more fully expand momentum for the full range of our Macintosh product line.'' The company said net income for the quarter was $ 140.5 million, 16 percent above the $ 121.4 million earned in the same period a year ago. Earnings per share for the quarter that ended Dec. 30 were $ 1.10, up from the 92 cents per share. Net sales were $ 1.4 billion, a 35 percent increase over the year-ago figure. International sales accounted for 32 percent of total revenues during the quarter, compared to 28 percent in the first quarter of fiscal 1988, according to a company statement. The company's profits rose 84 percent in the last fiscal year, exceeding analysts' expectations. `` The numbers were essentially in line with expectations,'' <PERSON> Lupatkin </PERSON> said of Tuesday's report. Regarding the announcement of the price cut, <PERSON> Lupatkin </PERSON> said the company could be `` repositioning existing products in anticipation of a new product introduction.'' `` I also think the price decline reflects the general slowing of overall industry growth,'' the analyst added. The company pointed to its commitment to new products in Tuesday's announcement.
