<HEAD>Ex-Employee Claims IBM Fired Him for Balking at South African Transfer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> employee, who claims he was fired for refusing a transfer to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, has filed a $ 25 million lawsuit against the computer giant. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khabo </PERSON>, a black naturalized <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen born in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, claimed he balked at the transfer to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> because he still faces charges for his anti-apartheid activities there. A former <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> marketing representative, <PERSON> Khabo </PERSON> sued the <LOCATION> Armonk </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based company earlier this week at federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, accusing <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> of alleged unlawful employment practices. On Tuesday, however, an <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman disputed <PERSON> Khabo </PERSON>'s claim. `` The termination was not related to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> was not an issue,'' said <PERSON> Theo </PERSON> <PERSON> Chisholm </PERSON> in a telephone interview. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> announced plans to sell its South African holdings to employees there in October 1986. Ms. <PERSON> Chisholm </PERSON> said that as of March 1987, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> had no assets or employees in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. She declined to say more, adding: `` We do n't comment on cases that are in litigation.'' According to <PERSON> Khabo </PERSON>'s lawsuit, he was hired by <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> in June 1984 and a year later, was asked to join South African students being trained to work at <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s division in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Khabo </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, resident with masters degrees in economics and business administration, claimed he told company officials that he could n't go back to his homeland unless the political system there changed. In 1963, when he was 16, according to the lawsuit, <PERSON> Khabo </PERSON> was twice arrested as a leader in the African Student Association. He was released the first time but sentenced to 21 months hard labor the second time. In 1975, according to court papers, <PERSON> Khabo </PERSON> _ who already was living in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ was named a co-conspirator in an alleged 1963 plot to overthrow the South African government. <PERSON> Khabo </PERSON> claimed that after he refused the transfer to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, he was passed over for assignment to a sales territory and was denied funds for courses to complete his doctorate, despite previous company promises to do so. In addition to <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, the lawsuit named four of <PERSON> Khabo </PERSON>'s former managers and <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> as co-defendants.
